POD1000000005_S0000337	for the vast majority of people they're not going into the designer boutique
POD1000000005_S0000338	they're going into a department store or a mass merchant
POD1000000005_S0000339	and you know those stores look at trend reports and they look at what's on the runway and part of their great ah skill in both marketing and manufacturing is being able to take those ideas and turn them around at just a rapid fire pace and get them into stores
POD1000000005_S0000340	and there isn't just one delivery that happens at the beginning of a season no no
POD1000000005_S0000341	it's a constant stream of newness
POD1000000005_S0000342	and when and when i say constant i mean like every two weeks for some of these places
POD1000000005_S0000343	so givhan says that at its best fast fashion means that new stylish clothes aren't just for fancies with the cash to shop haute couture
POD1000000005_S0000344	but i'm going to let you in on a little secret
POD1000000005_S0000345	it is impossible for clothing designers to go from original idea to brand spanking new product on the rack in two weeks
POD1000000005_S0000346	especially not at the volume that forever twenty-one needed to fill all of their bazillion stores
POD1000000005_S0000347	so the company had to find some shortcuts
POD1000000005_S0000348	copying other designers ideas was part of forever twenty-one's business model from the beginning
POD1000000005_S0000349	susan scafidi is the founder of the fashion law institute at fordham university and she basically invented the field of fashion law
POD1000000005_S0000350	and she'll be the first one to tell you that while forever twenty-one's practice of copying other designers ideas isn't a cute look it's generally totally legal
POD1000000005_S0000351	fashion is not recognized as an art form in the united states
POD1000000005_S0000352	so it doesn't get copyright protection in large part because a hundred years ago the copyright office decided that fashion no matter how fanciful was utilitarian
POD1000000005_S0000353	only a couple areas of fashion are protected from copying
POD1000000005_S0000354	we have a tiny bit of copyright protection at least since the nineteen sixties for two-dimensional elements of fashion things like fabric prints or lace designs
POD1000000005_S0000355	over on the patent side we've had historically a little bit of protection for some functional elements of fashion things like zippers and velcro and kevlar ah and space suits or hazmat suits
POD1000000005_S0000356	ah and then at the end of the day what fashion really has to rely on is trademark protection
POD1000000005_S0000357	that is protection for the logo or label
POD1000000005_S0000358	so basically the polo pony on your chest or the giant double g on your belt buckle those are protected
POD1000000005_S0000359	the design of the shirt and belt themselves are not original prints are generally also protected
POD1000000005_S0000360	while there aren't a ton of copyright and trademark protections for fashion in the u s
POD1000000005_S0000361	forever twenty-one has still found itself involved in many many many intellectual property lawsuits scafidi says they're one of the most egregious offenders in the game
POD1000000005_S0000362	gucci puma adidas anna sui diane von furstenberg and gwen stefani have all pursued legal action against forever twenty-one alleging various forms of copyright infringement
POD1000000005_S0000363	many smaller brands have also claimed their prints or designs were ripped off by the mega-retailer
POD1000000005_S0000364	but most didn't have the resources to go against a multi-billion dollar mammoth
POD1000000005_S0000365	and scafidi says fast fashion brands like forever twenty-one bank on that
POD1000000005_S0000366	a certain amount of copying is is baked into the business model of every fast fashion company
POD1000000005_S0000367	the only question is how literally they're copying and how much they're changing it up
POD1000000005_S0000368	in forever twenty-one's case they'd often barely bother to change anything about the original design they were ripping off
POD1000000005_S0000369	and some of their fabric prints were just a straight cut and copy job
POD1000000005_S0000370	and maybe on the back end you get caught and have to pay out the occasional settlement ah or or pay some legal fees
POD1000000005_S0000371	but usually that's cheaper ah than actually hiring designers and engaging in innovative product research
POD1000000005_S0000372	copying clothing designs hasn't been forever twenty-one's only questionable move
POD1000000005_S0000373	in two thousand one a workers advocacy center or filed lawsuit on behalf of employees who said they were made to work insane hours for way less than minimum wage
POD1000000005_S0000374	in twenty-twelve the u s department of labor sued the retailer for failing to pay federal minimum wage to its manufacturers and contractors
POD1000000005_S0000375	and in twenty-nineteen pop star ariana grande slapped forever twenty-one with a ten-million-dollar lawsuit
