POD1000000013_S0000107	that you're gonna continue to lead the office and do the job
POD1000000013_S0000108	thank you that's important
POD1000000013_S0000109	let's just move that's on a little bit and talk about human rights issues in relation to the actions of public services
POD1000000013_S0000110	you launched a brilliant human rights manual which sets out an approach that many ombudsmen in europe take
POD1000000013_S0000111	but it's not particularly prevalent in the united kingdom about actions that can be taken by an ombudsman
POD1000000013_S0000112	could you tell us a bit more about how you created this
POD1000000013_S0000113	well it was created jointly with the northern ireland human rights commission and it started as ever as as all good ideas with a conversation
POD1000000013_S0000114	and it was a conversation between the human rights commission and our office around the sort of case work that we were dealing with
POD1000000013_S0000115	we were dealing with issues like the roma community and feeling discriminated because they didn't have access to health services
POD1000000013_S0000116	we were dealing with issues of consent patients not giving consent to interventions and the family and the patient feeling excluded from the decision-making
POD1000000013_S0000117	but also we realised that ombudsmen and human rights commissions and and or equality bodies are actually doing the same job
POD1000000013_S0000118	so we mean ah my my style is to move on from the conversation and actually have a product
POD1000000013_S0000119	and the product was how to do this manual for ombudsman staff
POD1000000013_S0000120	how to introduce human rights principles into ombudsman investigations
POD1000000013_S0000121	and it's quite simple and it's not about strasbourg jurisprudence
POD1000000013_S0000122	that's the beauty of it i think for non-lawyers ah you know for for non-legal staff that they're they're very simple principles
POD1000000013_S0000123	participation a person affected by a decision by whatever public service provider be it health be it housing be it ah you know local government that they have to be able to participate
POD1000000013_S0000124	they have to be given enough information to participate effectively in the decision-making
POD1000000013_S0000125	so there's the principle of empowerment and the giving information
POD1000000013_S0000126	there's the principle of non-discrimination and being treated treated equally and fairly and having equal access
POD1000000013_S0000127	and ultimately like the fourth principle of the human rights-based approach is accountability and that's what we ombudsmen do
POD1000000013_S0000128	we hold public services to ah kind
POD1000000013_S0000129	and would you say that you've been able to hold public services more to account as a result of having that human rights-based approach
POD1000000013_S0000130	yes i think maladministration is a tool
POD1000000013_S0000131	but i think that having a human rights lens allows you to look more closely ah away so much from the process as to how the process actually affects the individuals and affects the individuals rights
POD1000000013_S0000132	so if give you an example we had a case where a young man died as a result of a a routine ear operation
POD1000000013_S0000133	and and it was a one-in-a-million reaction to a titanium implant to the packing around a titanium implant
POD1000000013_S0000134	the point being his his mum and dad believed that he wasn't consented for that intervention
POD1000000013_S0000135	the and and the thought was unfair and affected his human rights
POD1000000013_S0000136	the coroner had refused to undertake an inquest saying it didn't affect his human rights
POD1000000013_S0000137	when it came to my office we identified the human rights principle of participation
POD1000000013_S0000138	if i know what is gonna happen to me if i'm told of the risks ah instead of someone else making decision for me then my human rights have been respected
POD1000000013_S0000139	when i drew that out in the investigation report i i was able to come to a conclusion that ah where there was a it was a conflict between the experts
POD1000000013_S0000140	some said well another consultant might not have done the implant another said they would have they would have and they would have gone ahead with the implant
POD1000000013_S0000141	but actually the human rights-based approach meant that i thought about the individual and that they hadn't been properly consented
POD1000000013_S0000142	the result not only did the family get an investigation report identifying this issue but they were able to go to the coroner
POD1000000013_S0000143	he he's commenced an inquest
POD1000000013_S0000144	now you you have two things in northern ireland that we don't have you have a
POD1000000013_S0000145	partly because of your own excellence and bringing it about you have an integrated public service ombudsman scheme and you have the power of own initiative
POD1000000013_S0000146	are these valuable additions to the way ombudsmen should be working
POD1000000013_S0000147	i i do believe in the one-stop-shop model
POD1000000013_S0000148	the public services ombudsman in northern ireland and looks at complaints about government departments statutory agencies local government health and social care education schools universities colleges
POD1000000013_S0000149	i think that can be challenging for staff but i believe that they enjoy the variety
POD1000000013_S0000150	but i also believe that an ombudsman ombudsman principles of good administration apply across sectors
POD1000000013_S0000151	so yes i think it is the value
POD1000000013_S0000152	i think having one place to go to to seek redress for injustice is is important
POD1000000013_S0000153	if people don't want to go to court there's an ombudsman there that can look at the full range
POD1000000013_S0000154	own initiative is for me an essential tool of every ombudsman's toolkit
POD1000000013_S0000155	when you look internationally
POD1000000013_S0000156	you look at ombudsmen in australia you look at ombudsmen in europe you look at ombudsmen north america the ontario ombudsmen the rest western australian ombudsmen
POD1000000013_S0000157	they all have own initiative they've all had own initiative from the start
POD1000000013_S0000158	the irish ombudsmen act that was created in nineteen eighty had own initiative there as well as dealing with individual complaints
POD1000000013_S0000159	for me an ombudsman without own initiative can't fulfill the the the mandate of ah ah ah improving public services for many not just for the individual
POD1000000013_S0000160	um so you would you you'd have no hesitation about introducing and initiative it's essential
POD1000000013_S0000161	not not at all i was lucky to be part of the development of the public services ombudsman act
POD1000000013_S0000162	and was keen to had had an opportunity to persuade officials who were perhaps nervous about the an ombudsman having own initiative powers
POD1000000013_S0000163	that really this was something that actually could benefit public services in the end
POD1000000013_S0000164	see it is about prevention
POD1000000013_S0000165	you can deal with numerous complaints but never get to the core issue whereas own initiative allows you to tackle the core issue of systemic failing
POD1000000013_S0000166	well i i agree with that
POD1000000013_S0000167	and that's why i think it's necessary for us to have the reform that you've already been operating for nearly three years now
POD1000000013_S0000168	yes and now ah the welsh ombudsman is about to get that also
POD1000000013_S0000169	i believe scottish ombudsman would like own initiative
POD1000000013_S0000170	so if that happens it means devolved administrations have it
POD1000000013_S0000171	and the first ever ombudsman in these islands the parliamentary ombudsman has not
POD1000000013_S0000172	and i think that's missing an opportunity to to improve public services for the citizen
POD1000000013_S0000173	as you move on from the public service ombudsman what what are you most proud of
POD1000000013_S0000174	is it bringing the whole thing together the integration of the various systems
POD1000000013_S0000175	well i think the legislation that allowed the public services ombudsman as a one-stop-shop for complaints about public services
POD1000000013_S0000176	but also being able to bring in local government standards
POD1000000013_S0000177	because northern ireland was one of the was the only part in europe didn't have a mandatory code of conduct for local representatives
POD1000000013_S0000178	that was introduced in two thousand and fourteen
POD1000000013_S0000179	and my office and my so and and i as deputy ombudsman now ombudsman have been key to establishing an investigative and judicative function in northern ireland
