POD1000000015_S0000096	multitasking to do
POD1000000015_S0000097	they have multitasking to do and they are incredible set of people my investigators
POD1000000015_S0000098	but i think one of the things that drives us and that is probably the the uniting thing is very much about values
POD1000000015_S0000099	and i think like most ombudsman organisations i've ever come across um it's a fairly unique workforce i would say
POD1000000015_S0000100	because you ask anybody why we're there and very rarely will you deviate far from because we want to make a difference because we want to see improvement because we want to make things better
POD1000000015_S0000101	so yes it's a challenge having the scope and we have some individuals who may have a background in a particular area but we don't have specialists
POD1000000015_S0000102	okay now what you have which we don't have is the status of being a complaints standards authority
POD1000000015_S0000103	could you explain to our listeners briefly what that means
POD1000000015_S0000104	briefly what it means is the ombudsman is responsible for setting a model complaints handling process that all scottish bodies must follow
POD1000000015_S0000105	and we then with that have a duty to monitor performance in relation to complaint handling and combined with some of our other powers duty to enforce good practice to report on it
POD1000000015_S0000106	now that sounds you know oh that's nice model complaints handling
POD1000000015_S0000107	but what it means in practice is with some slight variations by sector um because different sectors have slightly different needs
POD1000000015_S0000108	it means that anybody making a complaint to a public body in scotland and about a public body in scotland is basically making a complaint under the same set of standards
POD1000000015_S0000109	so the model complaints handling process says that the first stage of a complaint you must try and respond within five working days to resolve it
POD1000000015_S0000110	very big focus on resolution
POD1000000015_S0000111	if you can't or the person is not satisfied you can then take another twenty working days to look at it in more detail
POD1000000015_S0000112	if it's something that you think you need more than twenty days for then talk to the complainer about that
POD1000000015_S0000113	but it essentially means that if somebody does not receive a response or doesn't receive a response in time they get to the ombudsman a lot quicker than they might otherwise do
POD1000000015_S0000114	the other benefit of the complaints model complaints handling process is that there is a very strong focus on learning from complaints
POD1000000015_S0000115	so the standards that go with this which incidentally i have to lay before the scottish parliament the standards
POD1000000015_S0000116	they also have a very strong bent on learning from complaints
POD1000000015_S0000117	and i think that's an area where we can perhaps develop more in how we hold public bodies to account to demonstrate that learning
POD1000000015_S0000118	because like our complaints the model complaints handling we have to show that there is an impact and that there is value to individuals and to public services as a whole
POD1000000015_S0000119	ah i think for me the the most valuable thing about it though is it gives you an opportunity to work with public bodies not always in opposition to them
POD1000000015_S0000120	which with the best will in the world however much you try a resolution or a a a sort of discursive way of looking at complaints
POD1000000015_S0000121	once a complaint has reached the ombudsman it is in many ways adversarial whether you want it to be or not
POD1000000015_S0000122	but when you're talking about complaint handling as a whole you have an opportunity actually to help public bodies
POD1000000015_S0000123	and encourage them to get better at complaint handling which you hope means they get better at learning from complaints
POD1000000015_S0000124	which means people get the right service the first time
POD1000000015_S0000125	i don't think we'll ever eliminate complaints but certainly it it hopefully will make it a more productive experience
POD1000000015_S0000126	now i i'm a full supporter of what you're doing
POD1000000015_S0000127	i'm a burglar of your practice when i was the higher education ombudsman i stole it hook line and sinker to use in english universities
POD1000000015_S0000128	the idea that they could resolve complaints within five days was anathema to them they wouldn't they wouldn't have that we ended up with ninety
POD1000000015_S0000129	but ah nevertheless they they did it
POD1000000015_S0000130	but the difference and the the radical nature of what you do is effectively you are a regulator now
POD1000000015_S0000131	whereas ombudsman have traditionally always said we rely on our moral authority not on a coercive power
POD1000000015_S0000132	has that made a difference or is it just words
POD1000000015_S0000133	no i i don't think it makes is made a difference yet
POD1000000015_S0000134	i i also think i should add that i wasn't ombudsman when the complaints standards authority came in
POD1000000015_S0000135	yeah
POD1000000015_S0000136	and credit has to go to jim martin my predecessor for driving this yeah
POD1000000015_S0000137	yeah
POD1000000015_S0000138	what he's left me as a legacy is something really good to develop and work with which is what we're doing now
POD1000000015_S0000139	having been information commissioner which really is a regulatory function you your decision is binding or you go to court
POD1000000015_S0000140	i think the concept of regulation probably hasn't crept into our thinking with complaints standards in quite the same way
POD1000000015_S0000141	but it is something that we currently developing but maybe not calling it regulation in the same way
POD1000000015_S0000142	because one of the things that i would say learning from hindsight is that we took a very structured approach of rolling it out sector by sector this model complaints handling
POD1000000015_S0000143	and what that meant was it was a number of years before every public body in scotland was following this
POD1000000015_S0000144	so the n h s was the last and that's been the last just coming up to the end of their second year
POD1000000015_S0000145	now if you compare that to the first which was local government
POD1000000015_S0000146	local government now is a really high percentage of complaints get ah responded to in the first instance in the five working days
POD1000000015_S0000147	ah i think from memory it's it's over eighty percent and that's really significant for complainers
POD1000000015_S0000148	now what we've been looking at in the last few months and we went live with in april is what we've called our support and intervention policy
POD1000000015_S0000149	and this is a a concept that i brought with me from being information commissioner
POD1000000015_S0000150	and and basically was looking at all the powers that you have as an ombudsman because the real value comes in the combination of them not just the individual bits
POD1000000015_S0000151	so when you look at the powers to set complaint handling processes to take action if complaint handling falls short you then look at other things like your information gathering powers
POD1000000015_S0000152	we've created a framework which sets out what our powers are and within that what we are going to do to either support or if necessary intervene
POD1000000015_S0000153	because when we for example a simple example we might see a number of complaints from a public body where the final response that they give to the complainer does not signpost the ombudsman
POD1000000015_S0000154	they have a duty to do that under the complaints handling process
