POD1000000028_S0000030	this is heavy medals from thirty for thirty podcasts i'm alyssa roenigk gymnastics has been part of my life in some form for as long as i can remember from watching mary lou on t v at the nineteen eighty-four olympics when i was seven too later being a teenage gymnast obsessing over kim zmeskal's tumbling passes
POD1000000028_S0000031	and for the past fifteen years at e s p n where my reporting partner bonnie ford and i both cover international sports
POD1000000028_S0000032	when i covered my first summer olympic games in beijing in two thousand and eight china was accused of having an underaged gymnast on the team and i was writing about it i'll never forget bela karolyi shouting into my digital recorder about how the chinese coaches had just stolen his playbook
POD1000000028_S0000033	i wish i still had that tape here was bela karolyi not just upset that china had possibly broken the rules but wanting to make sure i knew he deserved credit for recognizing that younger and smaller gymnasts had better chances for gold it was a point he'd been making to reporters for years
POD1000000028_S0000035	as the truth has come to light about the consequences of pinning a nation's hopes on the shoulders of children bela and martha karolyi have come under scrutiny
POD1000000028_S0000036	today breaking news allegations that strike at the heart of a very successful u s olympic sport
POD1000000028_S0000037	one of the worst things we have seen in u s olympic history
POD1000000028_S0000038	their legacy is littered with questions about what they accomplished and how much responsibility they bear for the incredible amount of damage that has been done
POD1000000028_S0000039	claims tonight from a former gymnast who has filed suit against a doctor and legendary coaches bela and martha karolyi
POD1000000028_S0000040	yes this unnamed gymnast accuses the karolyis of turning a blind eye to abuse
POD1000000028_S0000041	but as complicated as their story would become it all started with something simple
POD1000000028_S0000043	it started with perfection
POD1000000028_S0000045	at the nineteen seventy six olympic games in montreal fourteen-year-old nadia comaneci earned the first perfect ten in olympic gymnastics history
POD1000000028_S0000046	and when the judges announced her score the crowd erupted but no one more so than nadia's coach bela karolyi
POD1000000028_S0000047	at thirty three years old bela and martha karolyi were just beginning their career as coaches outside of romania they were unknowns but bela was impossible to miss
POD1000000028_S0000048	especially as the six foot plus coach towered over his four foot eleven eighty-six pound protege
POD1000000028_S0000050	over the course of a single thrilling week nadia became the crowd favorite and an international star as she scored perfect ten after perfect ten
POD1000000028_S0000052	an unbelievable seven perfect tens all together and in the individual all around nadia won the gold medal a first for romania
POD1000000028_S0000053	finally nadia comes up and does her incredible routine that's where the crowd exploded i mean there was explosion explosion of support explosion of love and excitement and i'm looking through the corner of my eyes
POD1000000028_S0000054	and i see the soviet team getting they stuff and they walking out of the arena i said yes yes we got it
POD1000000028_S0000055	finally after decades of dominance a romanian had beaten the soviets
POD1000000028_S0000056	in a way for some people this is the end of a love affair the dethroning of the u s s r gymnastic competition nadia comaneci now takes over the fourteen-year-old sprite of a girl
POD1000000028_S0000057	but for bela karolyi and his wife and coaching partner martha there was something even greater at stake the favor of the romanian government
POD1000000028_S0000060	it was late night on the romanian time so i was watching it with our team doctor and his wife martha's friend and my wife we watched on a black and white t v
POD1000000028_S0000062	my name is geza pozsar that's the hungarian pronunciation in english is like gee za po za so geza pozsar
POD1000000028_S0000063	geza pozsar was the choreographer for the romanian national team
POD1000000028_S0000064	he'd been working with bela and martha for years he'd designed nadia's floor routine and helped her train for this moment but instead of watching from the sidelines with bela and martha he was watching from home because the romanian government wouldn't let him travel to montreal
POD1000000028_S0000065	because i didn't get the visa to go
POD1000000028_S0000066	geza had recently married a french woman and so the government didn't trust him to go to canada and actually return to romania
POD1000000028_S0000068	from his living room in the small town of onesti geza like the rest of romania watched nadia make history
POD1000000028_S0000070	the whole town came out to the street it was like midnight all of them they come out and this was like a carnival in rio you know it was unbelievable first off they get drunk you know that was the first thing but everyone was so happy
POD1000000028_S0000071	and and there was a huge celebration huge
POD1000000028_S0000072	but this moment was bigger than just the party in those small town streets
POD1000000028_S0000073	the whole world was in ecstasy you know
POD1000000028_S0000074	the whole world was in ecstasy that's why nadia's perfect tens and her gold medal were so important they made romania visible a country that suddenly stood out from the rest of the communist bloc
POD1000000028_S0000075	nadia was a lovable figure from a place the western world saw as very grim
POD1000000028_S0000076	nadia was the diamond she was the treasure of romania she was the best product romania ever had nadia put romania on the map after nadia everybody knows that there is the romania
POD1000000028_S0000078	during the cold war sports were a way for nations to assert their power without going to war olympic success equaled national pride for athletes and coaches in romania it meant security and stature it meant not waiting in line for a loaf of bread
POD1000000028_S0000079	people suffer from shortages
POD1000000028_S0000080	brought about by despotism and corruption of the imperial government
POD1000000028_S0000081	and romania at that time was under a very very strict ugly dictatorship and it was a cult of personality
POD1000000028_S0000082	public display of giant portraits of communist leaders
POD1000000028_S0000083	we had to idolize the leader of the country
POD1000000028_S0000084	nadia's win was the ultimate political validation for the country's leader nicolae ceausescu
POD1000000028_S0000085	the pageantry was befitting the crowning of a princess
POD1000000028_S0000086	there was a national celebration the president got very excited
POD1000000028_S0000087	the presentation was made personally by the president of romania nicolae ceausescu
POD1000000028_S0000089	nadia and the karolyis were welcomed home to romania as heroes
POD1000000028_S0000090	they gave us awards you know we got um some bonuses we paid only half of the tax like everybody paid we got fifty percent deduction on our taxes
POD1000000028_S0000091	propaganda is power in a regime like ceausescu's and there was no better propaganda than celebrating and rewarding the success of its olympic champion and the coaches who had brought romania such high honor
POD1000000028_S0000092	nadia was made a hero of the socialist country and she was a hero all decorated
POD1000000028_S0000093	her country honored nadia with its highest award the hero of the socialist labor
POD1000000028_S0000094	she got the car bela got two cars
POD1000000028_S0000095	nadia and the karolyis were gifted cars their taxes were cut in half as the rest of the country dealt with crushing rations the romanian coaches and their choreographer had meals delivered to them for free
POD1000000028_S0000096	the days of waiting in food lines were over for them
POD1000000028_S0000097	the only thing that they all expected us to do is to win medals
POD1000000028_S0000098	as long as they could keep making romania proud
POD1000000028_S0000100	bela karolyi had always been an athlete but never a gymnast
POD1000000028_S0000101	he was a boxer in the beginning then he became a hammer thrower then he became a handball coach so everything but gymnastics
POD1000000028_S0000102	bela's first experience with gymnastics didn't come until college
POD1000000028_S0000103	i had to pass some gymnastic test which was all difficult to me i was a tall and pretty heavy guy
POD1000000028_S0000104	so it was it was something something to to see me ah swinging on the bars and doing a tumbling which was an unknown sport for me totally unknown before
POD1000000028_S0000105	he was introduced to gymnastics and to one of his classmates martha eross the woman he would marry
POD1000000028_S0000106	i got married and my wife a former gymnast she was a good gymnast though we got married and we went out to teach the gymnastics
POD1000000028_S0000107	martha and bela both majored in physical education with the goal of coaching young kids they wanted to work together and decided to focus on her specialty gymnastics
POD1000000028_S0000108	it was a new experience totally new experience for me i never had the experience to teach young children i didn't know how to to start with them
POD1000000028_S0000109	bela came to the sport not knowing much about gymnastics but that didn't really matter because he was essentially teaching himself the basics of the sport by teaching little kids who didn't know much about gymnastics themselves
POD1000000028_S0000110	that's something geza noticed the first time he saw bela in action
POD1000000028_S0000111	i saw this big guy big guy ah dressed in a blue warmup and some very small little kids who were up almost just up to his hips you know
POD1000000028_S0000112	flipping like they're little fishes in the water you know like little silver fishes tumbling on the floor it was very impressive and i saw this guy with huge hands you know sometimes spotting them and throwing them up in the air and catching them and
POD1000000028_S0000113	oh my god this guy there was something different
POD1000000028_S0000114	it was kind of an ideal match giant bela could easily spot these small kids and help them safely learn new skills his wife martha had the gymnastics know how and credibility
POD1000000028_S0000115	they started to teach very young kids very hard tricks easy to spot them you know
POD1000000028_S0000116	the karolyis refined their system in local gymnasiums for ten years before breaking onto the national stage
POD1000000028_S0000117	after that he ah got in connection with the ah gymnastic federation ah they get lots of help from ah them
POD1000000028_S0000118	bela and martha's approach got results nearly all of the athletes on the romanian olympic team that won the silver medal in nineteen seventy-six had trained with the karolyis
POD1000000028_S0000119	as a group they were noticeably younger and tinier than the gymnasts who had come before them
POD1000000028_S0000120	fourteen-year-old nadia comaneci of romania four feet eleven eighty-six pounds
POD1000000028_S0000121	by comparison the nineteen seventy-two olympic gold medalist was a nineteen-year-old the nineteen sixty-eight gold medalist was twenty-six they'd been through puberty they were taller they had women's bodies
POD1000000028_S0000122	when nadia won gold at fourteen years old it sealed the trend toward child athletes
POD1000000028_S0000123	the youngest ever to win a gold medal in the all around competition
POD1000000028_S0000124	nadia congratulations again and i one thing i wanted to ask she's the youngest girl to win a gold medal at the olympic games where does she go from here what what about nineteen eighty
POD1000000028_S0000127	i'm going to participate at the olympics in moscow and i'm going to try to do better than i did here and learn a lot new things
POD1000000028_S0000128	how many more tens does she expect
POD1000000028_S0000130	as many as possible
POD1000000028_S0000131	congratulations and to your coach bela karolyi
POD1000000028_S0000132	before the nineteen seventy-six games were even over the romanians were focused on repeating and adding to that success and because bela was seen as responsible for nadia
POD1000000028_S0000133	the romanian government put the karolyis in charge of a new national training center in the small industrial town of deva
POD1000000028_S0000134	bela always like to ah work in this type of a small places when he had lots of control
POD1000000028_S0000135	it was isolated that was the point bela liked to keep tabs on the girls
POD1000000028_S0000136	so he knew when the girls went to buy some ice cream or ah he knew because he knew everybody so the girls were under control they could not go and buy food or something without him knowing it
POD1000000028_S0000137	geza had moved to deva with bela and martha to continue as the team's choreographer and dance coach they were working at the pinnacle of romania's centralized system
POD1000000028_S0000138	and there was tremendous pressure to find more nadias
POD1000000028_S0000139	my real full name is ah gertrude emilia eberle
POD1000000028_S0000140	trudi kollar was a gymnast for romania's national team from nineteen seventy-six to nineteen eighty-three she competed under her middle and maiden names emilia eberle
POD1000000028_S0000141	because it sounded more like romanian
POD1000000028_S0000142	by age twelve trudi was the reigning junior national champion
POD1000000028_S0000143	i just got a call at home
POD1000000028_S0000144	it was bela karolyi
POD1000000028_S0000145	i saw nadia on t v and i loved gymnastics and i said i always told my mom my gosh i wish i could train with her but that's never gonna happen and then we get a phone call and i was like i said okay mom let's go
POD1000000028_S0000146	trudi traveled with her mother by train to deva
POD1000000028_S0000147	i was so happy when we got there and i saw bela he was he looked to me like a mountain i was a little tiny girl and he was like big and all smiling and everything
POD1000000028_S0000148	her mother kissed her and placed a half a loaf of bread in a dresser drawer before leaving she told her daughter to please remember to eat
POD1000000028_S0000149	she said okay honey i need to leave now i need to catch a train i said bye mom i gave her a kiss and then bela showed her to the through the hallway to the door
POD1000000028_S0000150	and i was just like oh okay by myself in a room i said okay so where should i put my stuff and the door just suddenly opens ah ah in a scary way and you know just really fast
POD1000000028_S0000151	and bela comes in and he smacked me over the face so hard that i flew on my bed and he opened the drawer where my bread was in and he said if i ever see you again eating anything like this i will kill you
POD1000000028_S0000152	that was my welcome
POD1000000028_S0000154	don't misunderstand the national training center at a drab town called deva is not a concentration camp there are pillow fights and fun and going to school but there's mostly training
POD1000000028_S0000155	and tough training it is this was nadia in her training days with coach karolyi standing by but not catching her is this training or torture and what did the youngsters think about
POD1000000028_S0000156	we've felt watched all the time
POD1000000028_S0000157	gaby geiculescu was thirteen years old when she was recruited to train with trudi and the other olympians in the making
POD1000000028_S0000158	life in deva was one of deprivation beatings and living in constant fear
POD1000000028_S0000159	i tell you what i what i saw when i got there you know two little crackers in the morning it was a little food but it was not enough
POD1000000028_S0000160	i mean i ate toothpaste because i was not able to sleep i was so hungry and i just tell them i need something in my stomach
POD1000000028_S0000161	we were eating leftovers on the street if you find a little apple that it was like half-eaten then you would pick it up
POD1000000028_S0000162	you you fall asleep dreaming about chocolates floating in front of your eyes you fall asleep seeing like fried chicken
POD1000000028_S0000163	especially when you go on the coaches eat to a table next to you and they get like fried chicken and french fries and they eat right next to us and we sit there what we have
POD1000000028_S0000164	a yogurt a plain yogurt and a boiled egg or you have a dry piece of meat that gets stuck in your throat it's so dry
POD1000000028_S0000165	i mean you you go to sleep hungry and with all that training you know training training training and we were given a fist of vitamins or who knows what was that
POD1000000028_S0000166	and we never knew what's gonna happen next and there were times where eleven o'clock at night came and bela came to the dorm and said put your shoes on and let's go start running outside you're fat as pigs
POD1000000028_S0000168	go run rain shine snowing
POD1000000028_S0000169	there was no patience or compassion for injuries at bela's training center
POD1000000028_S0000170	he wanted everything fast quick you know put them back together fast you know if the doctor doesn't didn't follow bela's orders you know they are out
POD1000000028_S0000171	bela fired doctors who didn't follow his orders and the gymnasts knew that complaining about injuries could lead to a beating
POD1000000028_S0000172	one day doing a vault at practice gaby landed awkwardly and broke two fingers she walked back to her teammates and showed them her throbbing right hand
POD1000000028_S0000173	and they told me shut up don't say anything because he's gonna get so mad and i had to finish that practice with two broken fingers
POD1000000028_S0000174	i remember trying to grab the bar with the one one of the hands i couldn't put two fingers down and somehow he just got kind of sick of looking at me not doing a good job
POD1000000028_S0000175	he said few words you know and and just just dismissed me nobody's gonna take me to take an x-ray not have a doctor to look at this
POD1000000028_S0000176	and all what i hear from colleagues is just keep going
POD1000000028_S0000177	everything about the gymnasts lives in deva was monitored the national team coaches listened to their phone calls and intercepted their mail
POD1000000028_S0000178	when homesick girls ran away from the training center police took them back to deva
POD1000000028_S0000179	i was so scared i swear i thought he has eyes on trees and the bushes on the walls
POD1000000028_S0000180	we couldn't quit it was not a choice and you had to keep going against your will against everything
POD1000000028_S0000181	bela maintained complete control while martha came into the gym mostly to coach balance beam
POD1000000028_S0000182	to me it always seemed like he was always on top of everything and she was doing whatever he wanted her to do and obeying everything
POD1000000028_S0000183	when martha was in the gym she could also be physically abusive
POD1000000028_S0000184	and we could actually defend ourselves from her because she was not strong enough to catch us and hit us
POD1000000028_S0000185	so you know something like she was scratch us or and she would grab us from the neck like this and then she would pull her fingernails into your meat and it kinda hurt but she was she was not good at beating
POD1000000028_S0000186	bela was the bad one oh gosh that was bad
POD1000000028_S0000187	and when they faltered at meets they faced his wrath
POD1000000028_S0000188	let's say on beam you fell on beam that was a disaster you got off the beam saluted the judges and we went straight to the bathroom and he came after us and we got beaten up
POD1000000028_S0000190	and then he said well you better pull yourself together because you have two more events
POD1000000028_S0000191	the girls only respite from bela and martha was their dance classes with geza
POD1000000028_S0000192	you know it was relaxing for us it was fun he could ah make us you know smile and have a good time
POD1000000028_S0000193	they also knew he would look out for them
POD1000000028_S0000194	geza was always the one that was always behind bela's back he was protecting us
POD1000000028_S0000195	when he was together with bela and martha he was a tough guy because he had to look like a tough guy because he would have probably lost his job if he didn't
POD1000000028_S0000196	so every time we went to practice at the gym in the afternoon and geza was there before and he was always at the door looking through the keyhole and when bela and martha coming he said six six six and five five was martha and six was bela
POD1000000028_S0000197	geza used dance counts as code names for martha and bela
POD1000000028_S0000198	that's how we knew when he said six we already were like oh my gosh bela's coming
POD1000000028_S0000199	some days bela disappeared from the gym to go hunting
POD1000000028_S0000200	those are the best days of our lives in the gym so basically dracula wasn't there
POD1000000028_S0000201	who was dracula
POD1000000028_S0000202	oh bela
POD1000000028_S0000204	bela and martha faced enormous pressure going into the nineteen eighty olympics their standing with the government was only as good as their next result
POD1000000028_S0000205	they'd have to match or beat the success of the seventy-six games to keep their country's favor
POD1000000028_S0000206	the entire romanian team felt the weight of their country's oppressive regime when they met with officials before they left for moscow
POD1000000028_S0000207	some kind of lieutenant i don't know he was all dressed in green and stuff big and big guy and really serious and he said you better think what you're doing twice don't you ever bring shame on your country you're wearing our country on your shoulders
POD1000000028_S0000208	trying to defend her gold medal in the all-around nadia became the center of a judging dispute
POD1000000028_S0000210	nadia went on a beam and her beam score didn't come up
POD1000000028_S0000212	bela protested nadia's low beam score in full view of the television cameras
POD1000000028_S0000214	nadia had to settle for the silver in the all-around but went on to win gold on floor and beam trudi won a silver medal on the uneven bars
POD1000000028_S0000215	the romanians repeated with a silver in the team competition but this time finishing second to the russians was a disappointment bela and martha weren't returning to romania as heroes again
POD1000000028_S0000216	so when we made a big brouhaha about nadia's scoring on beam the government didn't like it
POD1000000028_S0000217	in a society hyper-sensitive about how it was perceived on the world stage and particularly by its communist allies bela's protest in response to the russian judge embarrassed the romanian officials
POD1000000028_S0000218	plus his most important ally in the ceausescu regime
POD1000000028_S0000219	had just been demoted
POD1000000028_S0000220	so ah bela knew that the end is close and then he told me at that moment we are now in big trouble and from there everything started to go sour for us
POD1000000028_S0000222	the first time i ever saw bela karolyi in action with his gymnasts was pretty memorable
POD1000000028_S0000224	it was the nadia eighty-one tour when bela and the romanian women's national team toured with the american team in march nineteen eighty-one
POD1000000028_S0000225	my reporting partner bonnie ford covered the detroit stop of the nadia eighty-one tour a seven-city promotional tour of the u s featuring the romanian national team and its superstar
POD1000000028_S0000226	so i personally as both an olympic fan and a reporter at that time i didn't think of it as a political event where the romanians were showing off their system so to speak
