POD1000000030_S0000001	if it saves energy and gives you performance a boost well when is a shoe just a shoe from american public media this is marketplace tech demystifying the digital economy i'm jack stewart in for molly wood
POD1000000030_S0000003	world athletics the governing body for track and field is set to announce whether it'll ban certain types of shoes
POD1000000030_S0000004	in particular nike's vaporfly shoes have been prominently on the feet of athletes responsible for tumbling race records recently
POD1000000030_S0000005	nike claims the two hundred and fifty dollars sneakers shave up to four percent off a runner's time so is that technology doping
POD1000000030_S0000006	we got hold of iain hunter professor of exercise science at brigham young university as he was with athletes training at b y u's indoor track he told us the shoes work by combining foam in the sole with a carbon fiber plate
POD1000000030_S0000007	i think the plate mostly allows for some structure of the shoes
POD1000000030_S0000008	so if that plate wasn't there and you have a forty-four millimeter height off the ground that's just foam and you try running around the corner that's just gonna collapse on you
POD1000000030_S0000009	so that the plate
POD1000000030_S0000011	mainly give structure to the shoe but it does give a small benefit in terms of energy cost
POD1000000030_S0000012	combine that with now you can do higher foam because you can hold everything together with the plate
POD1000000030_S0000013	and you've got a really good pushing into the ground a big displacement of the foot while it interacts with the ground and then pushes off really effectively
POD1000000030_S0000014	so it quite literally puts a spring in your step
POD1000000030_S0000015	yeah it it's not a coiled spring like we're used to but any foam is really a spring this one's just really effective at it
POD1000000030_S0000016	but where's the line that's what the question is now and i think these are either at the line where i'd feel comfortable or a little bit beyond
POD1000000030_S0000017	so you're saying that there could still so be some innovation allowed in shoes we're not going to say everybody must wear the same type of shoe but there must be a limit to it
POD1000000030_S0000018	yeah i i think it's wonderful to have the innovation on what nike has done as ah propel to other companies to catch up and they will catch up
POD1000000030_S0000019	so we could have the standard for marathoning or a road racing as a shoe like the vaporfly but then nike or someone will go a little further with it
POD1000000030_S0000020	and we'll end up with like sixteen millimeter foam and enough carbon fiber to hold the structure of it so you're not collapsing but it will just continue on
POD1000000030_S0000021	and the at some point the rules need to just standardize here's what a shoe is
POD1000000030_S0000022	the price of these shoes to us amateurs out there ah it seems incredibly high is it sort of what you would expect for a top-of-the-line running shoe
POD1000000030_S0000023	yeah when they say two hundred and fifty dollars for a pair of shoes that nike has mentioned probably will last year about ninety miles before it's losing some of its effectiveness
POD1000000030_S0000024	that is getting to the point of not outrageous but people are going to be restricted by the cost of that and they'll be looking for cheaper options
POD1000000030_S0000025	if new balance saucony others start competing with the same quality and performance of shoe and are charging a hundred and fifty nike is gonna have to start dropping their costs down
POD1000000030_S0000026	so i just the natural how marketing works and and it'll all come to an equilibrium over time
POD1000000030_S0000027	i remember reading about the advantages that some forms of artificial legs could give runners potentially over runners with like natural-born legs i mean are are we just reaching a point where kind of sport is hard engineering
POD1000000030_S0000028	it is and and i think it should be but there have to be some restrictions to how far you go
POD1000000030_S0000029	and we we don't want people to be tempted to amputate their lower legs so they can go from a two fifteen marathoner to a two o five marathoner
POD1000000030_S0000030	our legs aren't built just for running they're built for climbing and swimming and jumping and all kinds of activities
POD1000000030_S0000031	so if you tune the leg to be tuned just for running they'll be great at running but not good at other things
POD1000000030_S0000032	and that that's where you could go if you didn't have rules established
POD1000000030_S0000033	given that these shoes do kind of have a limited life do do athletes train in them and actually run in them in races or do you sort of hold them off for that that performance boost when you really need it
POD1000000030_S0000034	well if they're sponsored by nike they'll do all of their race pace work in those shoes
POD1000000030_S0000035	but if they're buying their own shoes what i typically see is they buy the pair do maybe two workouts in them before the race so they probably have about fifteen to twenty miles on them and then they do the race
POD1000000030_S0000036	and then they'll maybe workout in those ones but buy a new pair before the next race they do
POD1000000030_S0000037	and that's if it's someone that cares about saving a couple minutes on a marathon time
