YOU1000000003_S0000024	there are many many variants of neural networks and in recent years there's been sort of a boom in research toward these variants
YOU1000000003_S0000025	but in these two introductory videos you and i are just gonna look at the simplest plain vanilla form with no added frills
YOU1000000003_S0000026	this is a kind of a necessary pre-requisite for understanding any of the more powerful modern variants
YOU1000000003_S0000027	and trust me it's still has plenty of complexity for us to wrap our minds around
YOU1000000003_S0000028	but even in this simplest form it can learn to recognize handwritten digits
YOU1000000003_S0000029	which is a pretty cool thing for a computer to be able to do
YOU1000000003_S0000031	and at the same time you'll see how it does fall short of a couple hoops that we might have for it
YOU1000000003_S0000033	as the name suggests neural networks are inspired by the brain but lets break that down what are the neurons and in what sense are they linked together
YOU1000000003_S0000034	right now when i say neuron all i want you to think about is a thing that holds a number specifically a number between zero and one its really not more then that
YOU1000000003_S0000036	for example the network starts with a bunch of neurons co-responding to each of the twenty-eight times twenty-eight pixels of the input image
YOU1000000003_S0000037	which is seven hundred eighty-four neurons in total each one of these hold a number that represents the grey scale value of the corresponding pixel
YOU1000000003_S0000038	ranging from zero for black pixels up to one for white pixels this number inside the neuron is called it's activation
YOU1000000003_S0000039	and the image you might have in mind here is that each neuron is lit up when its activation is a high number
YOU1000000003_S0000041	so all of these seven hundred eighty four neurons make up the first layer of our network
YOU1000000003_S0000043	now jumping over to the last layer this has ten neurons each representing one of the digits
YOU1000000003_S0000044	the activation in these neurons again some number that's between zero and one
YOU1000000003_S0000045	represents how much the system thinks that a given image corresponds with the given digit
YOU1000000003_S0000046	there's also a couple of layer in between called the hidden layers which for the time being should just be a giant question mark
YOU1000000003_S0000047	for how on earth this process of recognizing digits is gonna be handled in this network i choose two hidden layers each one with sixteen neurons
YOU1000000003_S0000048	and admittedly that's kind of an arbitrary choice to be honest i choose two layers based on how i wanna motivate the structure in just a moment
YOU1000000003_S0000049	and sixteen well that was just a nice number to fit on the screen in practice there is a lot of room for experiment with this specific structure here
YOU1000000003_S0000050	the way the network operates activations in one layer determine the activations of the next layer
YOU1000000003_S0000051	and of course the heart of the network as an information processing mechanism comes down to exactly how those activations from one layer bring about activations in the next layer
YOU1000000003_S0000052	it's meant to be loosely analogous to have an biological networks of neurons some groups of neurons firing cause certain others to fire
YOU1000000003_S0000053	now the network i'm showing here has already been trained to recognize digits and let me show you what i mean by that
YOU1000000003_S0000054	it means if you feed in an image lighting up all seven hundred eighty-four neurons of the input layer according to the brightness of the each pixel in the image
YOU1000000003_S0000055	that pattern of activations causes some very specific pattern in next layer which causes some pattern in the one after it
YOU1000000003_S0000056	which finally give some pattern in the output layer and the brightest neuron of that output layer is the network's choice so to speak for what digit this image represents
YOU1000000003_S0000058	and before jumping into the math for how one layer influences the next or how training works
YOU1000000003_S0000059	let's just talk about why it's even reasonable to expect a layered structure like this to behave intelligently
YOU1000000003_S0000060	what are we expecting here what is the best hope for what those middle layers might be doing
YOU1000000003_S0000061	well when you or i recognize digits we piece together various components a nine has a loop up top and a line on the ray
YOU1000000003_S0000062	and eight also has a loop up top but its paired with another loop download
YOU1000000003_S0000063	a four basically breaks down into three specific lines and things like that
YOU1000000003_S0000064	now in a perfect world we might hope that each neuron in the second to last layer corresponds with one of these sub components
YOU1000000003_S0000065	that any time you feed in an image with say a loop up top like a nine or an eight there is some specific neuron whose activation is gonna be close to one
YOU1000000003_S0000066	and i don't mean this specific loop of pixels the hope would be that any generally loopy pattern towards the top sets off this neuron
YOU1000000003_S0000067	that way going from the third layer to the last one just requires learning which combination of sub-components corresponds to which digits
YOU1000000003_S0000068	of course that just kicks the problem down the road because how would you recognize these sub components who even learn what the right sub components should be
YOU1000000003_S0000069	and i still haven't even talked about how one layer influences the next but run with me on this one for a moment recognizing a loop can also break down into sub problems
YOU1000000003_S0000070	one reasonable way to do this would be the first recognize the various little edges that make it up
YOU1000000003_S0000071	similarly a long line like the kind you might seeing the digit one or four or seven well that's really a long edge or may be you think if it a certain pattern of several smaller edges
YOU1000000003_S0000072	so maybe our hope is that each neuron in the second layer of the network corresponds with the various relevant little edges
YOU1000000003_S0000073	maybe when an image like this one comes in it lights up all of the neurons associated with the around eight to ten specific little edges
YOU1000000003_S0000074	which in turn lights up the neurons associated with the upper loop and a long vertical line and those light up the neuron associated within nine
YOU1000000003_S0000075	whether or not this is what our final network actually does is another question when that i'll come back to once we see how to train the network
YOU1000000003_S0000076	but this is a hope that we might have a sort of goal with the layered structure like this
YOU1000000003_S0000077	more over you can imagine how being able to detect edges and patterns like this would be really useful for other image recognition tasks
YOU1000000003_S0000078	and even beyond image recognition there are all sort of intelligent things you might wanna do that breaks down into layers of abstraction
YOU1000000003_S0000079	parsing speech for example involves taking raw audio in picking out distinct sounds which combine to make certain syllables
YOU1000000003_S0000080	which combine to form words which combine to make up phrases and more abstracts dots et cetera
YOU1000000003_S0000081	but getting back to how any of this actually works picture yourself right now designing how exactly the activations in one layer might determine the activations in the next
YOU1000000003_S0000082	the goal is to have some mechanism that could conceivably combine pixels into edges or edges into patterns or patterns into digits
YOU1000000003_S0000083	and to zoom in on one very specific example but say the hope is for one particular neuron in the second layer
YOU1000000003_S0000084	to pickup on whether or not the image has an edge in this region here
YOU1000000003_S0000085	the question at hand is what parameters should the network have what dials and knobs should you be able to tweak
YOU1000000003_S0000086	so that it's expressive enough to potentially capture this pattern or any other pixel pattern or the pattern that several edges can make a loop and other such things
YOU1000000003_S0000087	what will we do is assign a weight to each one of the connections between our neuron and the neurons from the first layer
YOU1000000003_S0000088	these weights are just numbers then take all those activations from the first layer and compute their weighted sum according to these weights
YOU1000000003_S0000090	i find it helpful to think of these weights is being organized into a little grid of their own and i'm gonna use green pixels to indicate positive weights and red pixels to indicate negative weights
YOU1000000003_S0000091	where the brightness of that pixel is some loose depiction of the weight's value
YOU1000000003_S0000092	now if we made the weights associate with almost all of the pixels zero excepts for some positive weights in this region that we care about
YOU1000000003_S0000093	then taking the weighted sum of all the pixel values really just amounts to adding up the values of the pixel just in the region that we care about
YOU1000000003_S0000095	and if you really wanted to pickup on whether there's an edge here what you might do is have some negative weights associated with the surrounding pixels
YOU1000000003_S0000096	then the sum is largest when those middle pixels are bright but the surrounding pixels are darker
YOU1000000003_S0000098	when you compute a weighted sum like this you might come out with any number but for this network what we want is activations is to be some value between zero and one
YOU1000000003_S0000099	so a come thing to do is to pump this weight at sum in to some function that squishes the real number line into the range between zero and one
YOU1000000003_S0000100	and a common function that does this is called the sigmoid function also known as the logistic curve
YOU1000000003_S0000101	basically very negative inputs end up close to zero very positive inputs end up close to one and it just steadily increases around the input zero
YOU1000000003_S0000103	so the activation of the neuron here is basically in measure of how positive the relevant weighted sum is
YOU1000000003_S0000105	but maybe it's not that you want the neuron to light up when the weight at sum is bigger then zero maybe you only want it to be active when the sum is bigger then say ten
YOU1000000003_S0000106	that is you want some bias for it to be inactive
YOU1000000003_S0000107	what we do then is just add in some other number like negative ten to this weight at sum before plugging at through the sigmoid squishification function
YOU1000000003_S0000108	that additional number is called the bias
YOU1000000003_S0000109	so the weights tell you what pixel pattern this neuron in the second layer is picking up on and the bias tells you how high the weighted sum needs to be
YOU1000000003_S0000110	before the neuron starts getting meaningfully active
YOU1000000003_S0000111	and that is just one neuron every other neuron in this layer is gonna be connected to all seven hundred eighty four pixel neurons from the first layer
YOU1000000003_S0000112	and each one of those seven hundred eighty four connections has it's own weight associated with it
YOU1000000003_S0000113	also each one has sum bias some other number that you add on to the weighted sum before squishing it with the sigmoid
YOU1000000003_S0000114	and that's a lot to think about
YOU1000000003_S0000115	with this hidden layer of sixteen neurons that's a total of seven hundred eighty four times sixteen weights along with sixteen biases
YOU1000000003_S0000116	and all of that is just a connections from the first layer to the second the connections between the other layers also have a bunch of weights and biases associated with them
YOU1000000003_S0000117	all said and done this network has almost exactly thirteen thousand total weights and biases
YOU1000000003_S0000118	thirteen thousand knobs and dials they can be tweaked and turn to make this network behave in different ways
YOU1000000003_S0000120	so when we talk about learning what that's referring to is getting the computer to find a valid setting for all of these many many numbers so that it will actually solve the problem in hand
YOU1000000003_S0000122	one thought experiment that is a one's fun and kind a horrifying is to image sitting down and setting all of these weights and biases by hand
YOU1000000003_S0000123	purposely tweaking the numbers so that the second layer picks up on edges the third layer picks up on patterns et cetera
YOU1000000003_S0000124	i personally find this satisfying rather then just treating the network as a total black box
YOU1000000003_S0000125	because when the network doesn't perform the way you anticipate
YOU1000000003_S0000126	if you built up a little bit of relationship with what those weights and biases actually mean you have a starting place for experimenting with how to change the structure to improve
YOU1000000003_S0000127	or when the network does work but not for the reasons you might expect digging into what the weights and biases are doing is a good way to challenge your assumption
YOU1000000003_S0000128	and really expose the full space of possible solutions
YOU1000000003_S0000129	by the way the actual function here is a little come per sum to write down don't you think
YOU1000000003_S0000131	so let me show you an more notationally compact way that these connections are represented this is how you'd see if you choose to read at more about neural networks
YOU1000000003_S0000132	organize all of the activations from one layer into a column as a vector
YOU1000000003_S0000134	then organize all of the weights as a matrix where each row of that matrix corresponds to the connection between one layer and a particular neuron in the next layer
YOU1000000003_S0000135	what that means is that taking the weight at sum of the activations in the first layer according to these weights
YOU1000000003_S0000136	corresponds to one of the terms in the matrix vector product of everything we have on the left here
YOU1000000003_S0000138	by the way so much of machine learning just comes down to having a good grasp of linear algebra
YOU1000000003_S0000139	so for any of you who want a nice visual understanding from matrixes and what matrix vector multiplication means take a look at the series i did on linear algebra especially chapter three
YOU1000000003_S0000140	back to our expression instead of talking about adding the bias to each one of these values independently
YOU1000000003_S0000141	we represent it by organizing all those biases into a vector and adding the entire vector to the previous matrix vector product
YOU1000000003_S0000142	then as a final step i wrap a sigmoid around the outside here
YOU1000000003_S0000143	and what that suppose to represent is that you are gonna apply the sigmoid function to each specific component of the resulting vector inside
YOU1000000003_S0000144	so once you write down this weight matrix and these vectors as their own symbols you can communicate the full transition of activations for one layer to the next
YOU1000000003_S0000145	and in an extremely tight and neat little expression
YOU1000000003_S0000146	and this makes the relevant code both a lot simpler and a lot faster since many libraries optimize the hack out of matrix multiplication
YOU1000000003_S0000148	remember how earlier i said these neurons are simply things that hold numbers well of course the specific numbers that they hold depends on the image you feed in
YOU1000000003_S0000150	so it's actually more accurate to think of each neuron as a function when it takes in the outputs of all neurons in the previous layer and spits out a number between zero and one
YOU1000000003_S0000151	really the entire network is just a function when they takes in seven hundred eighty-four numbers as an input and spits out ten numbers as an output
YOU1000000003_S0000152	it's an absurdly complicated function one that involves thirteen thousand perimeters in the forms of these weights and biases that pick up on certain patterns
YOU1000000003_S0000153	and which involves iterating many matrix vector products and the sigmoid's squishification function
YOU1000000003_S0000154	but it's just the function nonetheless and in a way it's kind of reassuring that it looks complicated
YOU1000000003_S0000155	i mean if it were any simpler what hope would we have that it can take on the challenge of recognizing digits and how does it take on that challenge
YOU1000000003_S0000156	how does this network learn the appropriate weights and biases just by looking at data oh that's what i'll show in the next video
