YOU1000000102_S0000041	steve is also widely recognize for his ability to create an innovative environment inside apple as well as as an external company image that is equally innovative
YOU1000000102_S0000042	just think about apple's marketing campaigns over the past three decades a promotional flyer in nineteen seventy-six
YOU1000000102_S0000043	showed isak newton sitting under a tree just as an apple was falling by
YOU1000000102_S0000044	with the catchy exhortation to bite b y t e into an apple
YOU1000000102_S0000046	there was an iconic super bowl commercial
YOU1000000102_S0000048	techy humor
YOU1000000102_S0000050	an iconic super bowl commercial telling us that the macintosh was on the horizon
YOU1000000102_S0000051	and assuring us that we would see why nineteen eight-four wouldn't be like nineteen eight-four
YOU1000000102_S0000052	and in the late nineteen nineties we saw banners and billboards
YOU1000000102_S0000053	featuring pablo picasso albert einstein martha graham and mahatma gandhi all urging us to think different
YOU1000000102_S0000055	steve jobs understands the creativity and innovation start by thinking differently
YOU1000000102_S0000057	he has a deep routed belief in the power of education to transform lives coupled with desire to make the world a better place
YOU1000000102_S0000059	from the earliest days of apple he worked to develop partnerships with educators and get computers into schools
YOU1000000102_S0000061	for almost three decades he and his companies have provided invaluable technology in supports to schools and communities
YOU1000000102_S0000062	increasing accessibility to information for learners of all ages
YOU1000000102_S0000064	more than one hundred years ago in describing his vision for a new university lewan stanford wrote
YOU1000000102_S0000065	the imagination needs to be cultivated and developed to assure success in life
YOU1000000102_S0000067	stanford clearly understood the technical knowledge was only the starting point for creation and discovery
YOU1000000102_S0000068	steve jobs understands that the computer is a very powerful tool in a technical sense
YOU1000000102_S0000069	but that it's true power lies in the ability to unleash the imagination and creativity of the user
YOU1000000102_S0000071	as he explained to the new york times in a nineteen ninety-seven interview the macintosh turned out so well
YOU1000000102_S0000072	because the people working on it were musicians artists poets and historians
YOU1000000102_S0000073	who also happened to be excellent computer scientists
YOU1000000102_S0000075	and last fall a business week reporter asked how he manages for innovation
YOU1000000102_S0000076	his answer was deceptively simple we hire people who want to make the best things in the world
YOU1000000102_S0000078	steve jobs personifies the spirit and creativity that have characterized this university since it's founding one hundred and fourteen years ago
YOU1000000102_S0000079	and we're pleased to have him here today please join me in warmly welcoming this year's commandment speaker steve jobs
YOU1000000102_S0000081	i'm ah honored to be with you today for your commandment for one of the finest universities in the world
YOU1000000102_S0000083	truth be told
YOU1000000102_S0000085	ah i never graduate from college and ah this is the closest i've ever gotten to a college graduation
YOU1000000102_S0000087	today i wanna tell you three stories from my life that's it no big deal just three stories
YOU1000000102_S0000089	the first story is about connecting the docs
YOU1000000102_S0000091	i dropped out of re college after the first six months but then stayed around as a drop in for other eighteen months or so before i really quit
YOU1000000102_S0000093	so why'd i drop out
YOU1000000102_S0000095	it started before i was born
YOU1000000102_S0000097	my biological mother was a young unwed graduate student and she decided to put me up for adoption
YOU1000000102_S0000098	she felt very strongly that i should be adopted by college graduates so everything was all set for me to be adopted at birth by a lawyer and his wife
YOU1000000102_S0000100	except than when i popped out they decided at the last minute that they really wanted a girl
YOU1000000102_S0000102	so my parents who were on a waiting list got a call in the middle of the night asking we've got an unexpected baby boy you want him
YOU1000000102_S0000103	they said of course
YOU1000000102_S0000105	my biological mother found out later that my mother had never graduate from college and my father had never graduate from high school
YOU1000000102_S0000106	she refused to sign the final adoption papers
YOU1000000102_S0000108	she only relented a few months later when my parents promised that i would go to college this was the start in my life
YOU1000000102_S0000110	and seventeen years later i did go to college but i naively chose a college that was almost as expensive as stanford
YOU1000000102_S0000111	and all of my working class parents savings were being spent on my college tuition after six months i couldn't see the value in it
YOU1000000102_S0000112	i had no idea what i wanted to do with my life and no idea how college was going to help me figure it out
YOU1000000102_S0000113	and here i was spending all the money my parents had save their entire life
YOU1000000102_S0000115	so i decided to drop out and trust that it would all workout okay it was pretty scary at the time but looking back it was one of the best decisions i ever made
YOU1000000102_S0000117	the minute i dropped out i could stop taking the required classes that didn't interest me and begin dropping in on the ones that looked far more interesting
YOU1000000102_S0000119	it wasn't all romantic i didn't have a dorm room so slept on the floor in friend's rooms i returned cope bottles for five cent deposits to buy food with
YOU1000000102_S0000120	and i would walk the seven miles across town every sunday night to get one good meal a week at the hari krishna temple
YOU1000000102_S0000122	i loved it and much of what i stumbled into by following my curiosity and intuition turned out to be priceless later on let me give you one example
YOU1000000102_S0000124	reed college at that time offered perhaps the best calligraphy instruction in the country
YOU1000000102_S0000125	throughout the campus every poster every label and every drawer was beautifully hand calligraphed because i had dropped out
YOU1000000102_S0000126	and didn't have to take the normal classes i decided to take a calligraphy class to learn how to do this i learned about serif and sans-serif typefaces
YOU1000000102_S0000127	about varying the amount of space between different letter combinations about what makes great typography great
YOU1000000102_S0000129	it was beautiful historical artistically subtle in a way that science can't capture and i found it fascinating
YOU1000000102_S0000131	none of this had even a hope of any practical application in my life
YOU1000000102_S0000133	but ten years later when we were designing the first macintosh computer it all came back to me and we designed it all into the mac
YOU1000000102_S0000134	it was the first computer with beautiful typography if i had never dropped in on that single course in college
YOU1000000102_S0000135	the mac would have never had multiple typefaces or proportionally spaced fonts and since windows just copied the mac it's likely that no personal computer would have them
YOU1000000102_S0000137	if i had never dropped out i would have never dropped in on that calligraphy class and personal computers might not have the wonderful typography that they do
YOU1000000102_S0000138	of course it was impossible to connect the dots looking forward when i was in college but it was very very clear looking backwards ten years later
YOU1000000102_S0000139	again you can't connect the dots looking forward you can only connect them looking backwards so you have to trust that the dots will somehow connect in your future
YOU1000000102_S0000140	you have to trust in something your gut destiny life karma whatever because believing that the dots will connect
YOU1000000102_S0000141	down the road will give you the confidence to follow your heart even when it leads you off the well-worn path and that will make all the difference
YOU1000000102_S0000143	my second story is about love and loss
YOU1000000102_S0000145	i was lucky i found what i loved to do early in life woz and i started apple in my parent's garage when i was twenty we worked hard
YOU1000000102_S0000146	and in ten years apple had grown from just the two of us in a garage into a two billion dollar company with over four thousand employees
YOU1000000102_S0000147	we just released our finest creation the macintosh a year earlier and i just turned thirty
YOU1000000102_S0000149	and then i got fired
YOU1000000102_S0000151	how can you get fired from a company you started
YOU1000000102_S0000153	well as apple grew we hired someone who i thought was very talented to run the company with me and for the first year or so things went well
YOU1000000102_S0000154	but then our visions of the future began to diverge and eventually we had a falling out when we did our board of directors sided with him and so at thirty i was out
YOU1000000102_S0000155	and very publicly out what had been the focus of my entire adult life was gone and it was devastating
YOU1000000102_S0000157	i really didn't know what to do for a few months i felt that i had let the previous generation of entrepreneurs down that i had dropped the baton as it was being passed to me
YOU1000000102_S0000158	i met with david packard and bob noyce and tried to apologize for screwing up so badly
YOU1000000102_S0000160	i was a very public failure and i even thought about running away from the valley but something slowly began to dawn on me i still loved what i did
YOU1000000102_S0000162	the turn of events at apple had not changed that one bit i've been rejected but i was still in love
YOU1000000102_S0000164	and so i decided to start over
YOU1000000102_S0000166	i didn't see it then but it turned out that getting fired from apple was the best thing that could have ever happened to me
YOU1000000102_S0000167	the heaviness of being successful was replaced by the lightness of being a beginner again less sure about everything it freed me to enter one of the most creative periods of my life
YOU1000000102_S0000168	during the next five years i started a company named next another company named pixar and fell in love with an amazing woman who would become my wife
YOU1000000102_S0000169	pixar went on to create the world's first computer animated feature film toy story and is now the most successful animation studio in the world
YOU1000000102_S0000171	in a remarkable turn of events apple bought next and i returned to apple and the technology we developed at next is at the heart of apple's current renaissance
YOU1000000102_S0000172	and laureen and i have a wonderful family together
YOU1000000102_S0000174	i'm pretty sure none of this would have happened if i hadn't been fired from apple it was awful tasting medicine but i guess the patient needed it
YOU1000000102_S0000176	sometime life sometimes life's going to hit you in the head with a brick don't lose faith
YOU1000000102_S0000178	i'm convinced that the only thing that kept me going was that i loved what i did you've got to find what you love and that is as true for work as it is for your lovers
YOU1000000102_S0000179	your work is going to fill a large part of your life and the only way to be truly satisfied is to do what you believe is great work
YOU1000000102_S0000180	and the only way to do great work is to love what you do if you haven't found it yet keep looking
YOU1000000102_S0000182	and don't settle as with all matters of the heart you'll know when you find it and like any great relationship it just gets better and better
YOU1000000102_S0000183	as the years roll on so keep looking don't settle
YOU1000000102_S0000185	my third story is about death
YOU1000000102_S0000187	when i was seventeen i read a quote that went something like if you live each day as if it was your last someday you'll most certainly be right
YOU1000000102_S0000189	it made an impression on me and since then for the past thirty-three years i've looked in the mirror every morning and asked myself
YOU1000000102_S0000190	if today were the last day of my life what i want to do what i am about to do today and whenever the answer has been no for too many days in a row
YOU1000000102_S0000191	i know i need to change something
YOU1000000102_S0000193	remembering that i'll be dead soon is the most important tool i've ever encountered to help me make the big choices in life because almost everything
YOU1000000102_S0000194	all external expectations all pride all fear of embarrassment or failure these things just fall away in the face of death leaving only what is truly important
YOU1000000102_S0000195	remembering that you are going to die is the best way i know to avoid the trap of thinking you have something to lose you are already naked
YOU1000000102_S0000196	there is no reason not to follow your heart
YOU1000000102_S0000198	about a year ago i was diagnosed with cancer
YOU1000000102_S0000200	i had a scan at seven-thirty in the morning and it clearly showed a tumor on my pancreas i didn't even know what a pancreas was
YOU1000000102_S0000201	the doctors told me this was almost certainly a type of cancer that is incurable and that i should expect to live no longer than three to six months
YOU1000000102_S0000203	my doctor advised me to go home and get my affairs in order which is doctors code for prepare to die
YOU1000000102_S0000204	it means to try and tell your kids everything
YOU1000000102_S0000206	you thought you'd have the next ten years to tell them in just a few months it means to make sure everything is buttoned up so that will be as easy as possible for your family
YOU1000000102_S0000207	it means to say your goodbyes
YOU1000000102_S0000209	i live with that diagnosis all day later that evening i had a biopsy where they stuck an endoscope down my throat through my stomach and into my intestines
YOU1000000102_S0000210	put a needle into my pancreas and got a few cells from the tumor i was sedated but my wife who was there told me that when they viewed the cells under a microscope
YOU1000000102_S0000211	the doctor started crying because it turned out to be a very rare form of pancreatic cancer that is curable with surgery
YOU1000000102_S0000212	i had the surgery and thankfully i'm fine now
YOU1000000102_S0000214	this was the closest i've been to facing death and i hope it's the closest i get for a few more decades having lived through it
YOU1000000102_S0000215	i can now say this to you with a bit more certainty than when death was a useful but purely intellectual concept
YOU1000000102_S0000217	no one wants to die even people who want to go to heaven don't want to die to get there
YOU1000000102_S0000219	and yet death is the destination we all share no one has ever escaped it and that is as it should be
YOU1000000102_S0000220	because death is very likely the single best invention of life its life's change agent it clears out the old to make way for the new
YOU1000000102_S0000222	right now the new is you
YOU1000000102_S0000224	but some day not too long from now you will gradually become the old and be cleared away
YOU1000000102_S0000226	sorry to be so dramatic but it's quite true
YOU1000000102_S0000228	your time is limited so don't waste it living someone else's life don't be trapped by dogma which is living with the results of other people's thinking
YOU1000000102_S0000229	don't let the noise of others opinions drown out your own inner voice and most important have the courage to follow your heart and intuition
YOU1000000102_S0000230	they somehow already know what you truly want to become everything else is secondary
YOU1000000102_S0000232	when i was young there was an amazing publication called the whole earth catalog which was one of the bible's of my generation
YOU1000000102_S0000233	it was created by a fellow named stuart brand not far from here in menlo park and he brought it to life with his poetic touch
YOU1000000102_S0000234	this was in the late sixties before personal computers and desktop publishing so with all made with typewriters scissors and polaroid cameras
YOU1000000102_S0000235	it was sort of like google and paperback form thirty-five years before google came along it was idealistic overflowing with neat tools and great notions
YOU1000000102_S0000237	stuart and his team put out several issues of the whole earth catalog and then when it had run its course they put out a final issue
YOU1000000102_S0000238	it was the mid nineteen-seventies and i was your age
YOU1000000102_S0000240	on the back cover of their final issue was a photograph of an early morning country road
YOU1000000102_S0000242	the kind you might find yourself hitch hiking on if you were so adventurous beneath it were the words stay hungry stay foolish
YOU1000000102_S0000243	it was their farewell message as they signed off stay hungry stay foolish and i have always wished that for myself
YOU1000000102_S0000245	and now as you graduate to begin a new i wish that for you stay hungry stay foolish thank you all very much
