YOU1000000114_S0000001	hi gentlemen limping over the rules protect yourself at all the time follow my instructions
YOU1000000114_S0000003	touch guards if you wish come out ready to by
YOU1000000114_S0000008	ladies and gentleman referee herb dean has called a stop to this contest at four minutes fifty-seven seconds of round number two
YOU1000000114_S0000009	declaring the winner by team k o and now the new interim u f c feather weight champion of the world
YOU1000000114_S0000010	the notorious conor mcgregor
YOU1000000115_S0000000	how the economic machine works in thirty minutes
YOU1000000115_S0000002	the economy works like a simple machine but many people don't understand it or they don't agree on how it works
YOU1000000115_S0000003	and this has led to a lot of needless economic suffering
YOU1000000115_S0000005	i feel a deep sense of responsibility to share my simple but practical economic template
YOU1000000115_S0000007	though it's unconventional
YOU1000000115_S0000009	it has helped me to anticipate and to side-step the global financial crisis and it is worked well for me for over thirty years
YOU1000000115_S0000010	let's begin though the economy might seem complex it works in a simple mechanical way
YOU1000000115_S0000011	it's made up of a few simple parts and a lot of simple transactions that are repeated over and over again a zillion times
YOU1000000115_S0000012	these transactions are above all else driven by human nature and they create three main forces to drive the economy
YOU1000000115_S0000013	number one productivity growth number two the short term death cycle and number three the long term death cycle
YOU1000000115_S0000014	we'll look at these three forces and how laying them on top of each other creates a good template for tracking economic movements and figuring out what's happening now
YOU1000000115_S0000015	let's start with the simplest part of the economy transactions
YOU1000000115_S0000017	an economy is simply the sum of the transactions that make it up and a transaction is a very simple thing
YOU1000000115_S0000018	you make transactions all the time every time you buy something you create a transaction
YOU1000000115_S0000019	each transaction consists of a buyer exchanging money or credit with a seller for goods services or financial assets
YOU1000000115_S0000020	credit spends just like money so adding together the money spent and the amount of credit spent you could know the total spending
YOU1000000115_S0000021	the total amount of spending drives the economy
YOU1000000115_S0000022	if you divide the amounts spent by the quantity sold you get the price and that's it that's a transaction
YOU1000000115_S0000023	it's the building block of the economic machine
YOU1000000115_S0000024	all cycles and all forces in an economy are driven by transactions so if we can understand transactions we can understand the whole economy
YOU1000000115_S0000025	a market consists of all the buyers and all the sellers making transactions for the same thing
YOU1000000115_S0000026	for example there is a wheat market a car market the stock market and markets for millions of things
YOU1000000115_S0000027	an economy consists of all of the transactions in all of it's markets
YOU1000000115_S0000028	if you add up the total spending and the total quantity sold in the all of the markets you have everything you need to know to understand the economy
YOU1000000115_S0000029	it's just that simple
YOU1000000115_S0000030	people businesses banks and governments all engage in transactions the way i just described
YOU1000000115_S0000031	exchanging money and credit for goods services and financial assets
YOU1000000115_S0000032	the biggest buyer and seller is the government which consist of two important parts
YOU1000000115_S0000033	a central government that collects taxes and spends money and a central bank which is different from other buyers and sellers
YOU1000000115_S0000034	because it controls the amount of money and credit in the economy
YOU1000000115_S0000035	it does this by influencing interest rate and printing new money
YOU1000000115_S0000037	for these reasons as we'll see the central bank is an important player in the flow of credit
YOU1000000115_S0000038	i want you to pay attention to credit
YOU1000000115_S0000039	credit is the most important part of the economy and probably the least understood
YOU1000000115_S0000040	it's the most important part because it's the biggest and most volatile part
YOU1000000115_S0000042	just like buyers and sellers go to the market to make transactions so do lenders and borrowers
YOU1000000115_S0000043	lenders usually want to make their money in to more money and borrowers usually want to to buy something they can't afford
YOU1000000115_S0000044	like a house or a car or they want to invest in something like starting a business
YOU1000000115_S0000045	credit can help both lenders and borrowers get what they want
YOU1000000115_S0000046	borrowers promise to repay the amount they borrow called principle plus an additional amount called interest
YOU1000000115_S0000047	when interest rates are high there is less borrowing because it's expensive
YOU1000000115_S0000048	when interest rates are low borrowing increases because it's cheaper
YOU1000000115_S0000050	when borrowers promise to repay and lenders believe them credit is created
YOU1000000115_S0000052	any two people can agree to create credit out of thin air
YOU1000000115_S0000053	that seems simple enough but credit is tricky because it has different names
YOU1000000115_S0000054	as soon as credit is created it immediately turns in to debt
YOU1000000115_S0000055	debt is both an asset to the lender and a liability to the borrower
YOU1000000115_S0000057	in the future when the borrower repays the loan plus interest the asset and the liability disappear and the transaction is settled
YOU1000000115_S0000058	so why is credit so important
YOU1000000115_S0000060	because when a borrower receives credit he is able to increase his spending and remember spending drives the economy
YOU1000000115_S0000061	this is because one person's spending is another person's income
YOU1000000115_S0000062	think about it
YOU1000000115_S0000064	every dollar you spend someone else earns and every dollar you earn someone else has spent
YOU1000000115_S0000065	so when you spend more someone else earns more
YOU1000000115_S0000066	when someone's income rises it makes lenders more willing to lend him money because now he's more worthy of credit
YOU1000000115_S0000067	a creditworthy borrower has two things the ability to repay and collateral
YOU1000000115_S0000068	having a lot of income in relation to his debt gives him the ability to repay
YOU1000000115_S0000070	in the event that he can't repay he has valuable assets to use as collateral that can be sold this makes lenders feel comfortable lending him money
YOU1000000115_S0000071	so increased income allows increased borrowing which allows increased spending
YOU1000000115_S0000072	and since one person's spending is another person's income this leads to more increased borrowing and so on
YOU1000000115_S0000073	this self-reinforcing pattern leads to economic growth and is why we have cycles
YOU1000000115_S0000075	in a transaction you have to give something in order to get something and how much you get depends on how much you produce
YOU1000000115_S0000077	overtime we learn and that accumulated knowledge raises our living standards we call this productivity growth
YOU1000000115_S0000078	those who are inventive and hard-working raise their productivity and their living standards faster than those who are complacent and lazy
YOU1000000115_S0000079	but that isn't necessarily true over the short run
YOU1000000115_S0000080	productivity matters most in the long run but credit matters most in the short run
YOU1000000115_S0000081	this is because productivity growth doesn't fluctuate much so it's not a big driver of economic swings
YOU1000000115_S0000082	that is because it allows us to consume more than we produce when we acquire it and it forces us to consume less than we produce when we have to pay it back
YOU1000000115_S0000083	dead swings occur in two big cycles one takes about five to eight years and the other takes about seventy-five to a hundred years
YOU1000000115_S0000084	while most people feel the swings they typically don't see them as cycles because they see them too up close day by day week by week
YOU1000000115_S0000085	in this chapter we're going to step back and look at these three big forces and how they interact to make up our experiences
YOU1000000115_S0000086	as mentioned swings around the line are not due to how much innovation or hard work there is they are primarily due to how much credit there is
YOU1000000115_S0000087	let's for a second imagine an economy without credit in this economy the only way i can increase my spending is to increase my income
YOU1000000115_S0000088	which requires me to be more productive and do more work increased productivity is the only way for growth
YOU1000000115_S0000089	since my spending is another person's income the economy grows every time i or anyone else is more productive
YOU1000000115_S0000090	if we follow the transactions and play this out we see a progression like the productivity growth line but because we borrow we have cycles
YOU1000000115_S0000091	this isn't due to any laws or the regulations it's due to human nature and the way that credit works
YOU1000000115_S0000092	think of borrowing as simply a way of pulling spending forward in order to buy something you can't afford you need to spend more than you make
YOU1000000115_S0000093	to do this you essentially need to borrow from your future self in doing so you create a time in the future that you need to spend less than you make
YOU1000000115_S0000094	in order to pay it back it very quickly resembles a cycle basically anytime you borrow you create a cycle
YOU1000000115_S0000095	this is as true for an individual as it is for the economy
YOU1000000115_S0000096	this is why understanding credit is so important because it set into motion a mechanical predictable series of events that will happen in the future
YOU1000000115_S0000097	this makes credit different from money money is what you settle transactions with
YOU1000000115_S0000098	when you buy a beer from a bartender with cash the transaction is settled immediately
YOU1000000115_S0000099	but when you buy a beer with credit it's like starting a bar tab you're saying you promise to pay in the future
YOU1000000115_S0000100	together you and the bartender create an asset and a liability you just created credit out of thin air
YOU1000000115_S0000101	it's not until you pay the bar tab later that the asset and the liability disappear the debt goes away and the transaction is settled
YOU1000000115_S0000103	the reality is that most of what people call money is actually credit
YOU1000000115_S0000104	the total amount of credit in the united states is about fifty trillion dollars and the total amount of money is only about three trillion dollars
YOU1000000115_S0000105	remember in an economy without credit the only way to increase your spending is to produce more
YOU1000000115_S0000106	but in an economy with credit you can also increase your spending by borrowing
YOU1000000115_S0000107	as a result an economy with credit has more spending and allows incomes to rise faster than productivity over the short run but not over the long run
YOU1000000115_S0000108	now don't get me wrong credit isn't necessarily something bad that just causes cycles
YOU1000000115_S0000109	it's bad when it finances over-consumption that can't be paid back
YOU1000000115_S0000110	however it's good when it efficiently allocates resources and produces income so you can pay back the debt
YOU1000000115_S0000111	for example if you borrow money to buy a big t v it doesn't generate income for you to pay back the debt
YOU1000000115_S0000112	but if you borrow money to say buy a tractor
YOU1000000115_S0000114	and that tractor let's you harvest more crops and earn more money then you can pay back your debt and improve your living standards
YOU1000000115_S0000116	and in an economy with credit we can follow the transactions and see how credit creates growth
YOU1000000115_S0000118	let me give you an example suppose you earn a hundred thousand dollars a year and have no debt you are credit worthy enough to borrow ten thousand dollars
YOU1000000115_S0000119	say on a credit card so you can spend a hundred and ten thousand dollars even though you only earn a hundred thousand dollars
YOU1000000115_S0000120	since your spending is another person's income someone is earning a hundred and ten thousand dollars
YOU1000000115_S0000121	the person earning a hundred and ten thousand dollars with no debt can borrow eleven thousand dollars so he can spend a hundred and twenty-one thousand dollars
YOU1000000115_S0000122	even though he has only earned a hundred and ten thousand dollars
YOU1000000115_S0000123	his spending is another person's income and by following the transactions we can begin to see how this process works in a self reinforcing pattern
YOU1000000115_S0000124	but remember borrowing creates cycles and if the cycle goes up it eventually needs to come down
YOU1000000115_S0000125	this leads us in to the short-term debt cycle
YOU1000000115_S0000127	as economic activity increases we see an expansion the first phase of the short-term debt cycle
YOU1000000115_S0000128	spending continues to increase and prices start to rise
YOU1000000115_S0000129	this happens because the increase in spending is fueled by credit which can be created instantly out of thin air
YOU1000000115_S0000130	when the amount of spending and incomes grow faster than the production of goods prices rise
YOU1000000115_S0000131	when prices rise we call this inflation the central bank doesn't want too much inflation because it causes problems
YOU1000000115_S0000132	seeing prices rise it raises interest rates with higher interest rates fewer people can afford to borrow money
YOU1000000115_S0000133	and the cost of existing debts rises think about this as the monthly payments on your credit card going up
YOU1000000115_S0000135	because people borrow less and have higher debt repayments they have less money left over to spend so spending slows
YOU1000000115_S0000136	and since one person's spending is another person's income incomes drop and so on and so forth
YOU1000000115_S0000137	when people spend less prices go down we call this deflation economic activity decreases
YOU1000000115_S0000138	and we have a recession if the recession becomes too severe an inflation is no longer a problem
YOU1000000115_S0000139	the central bank will lower interest rates to cause everything to pick up again
YOU1000000115_S0000140	with low interest rates debt repayments are reduced and borrowing and spending pick up and we see another expansion
YOU1000000115_S0000141	as you can see the economy works like a machine
YOU1000000115_S0000142	in the short-term debt cycle spending is constrained only by the willingness of lenders and borrowers to provide and receive credit
YOU1000000115_S0000143	when credit is easily available there is an economic expansion when credit isn't easily available there is a recession
YOU1000000115_S0000144	and note that this cycle is controlled primarily by the central bank
YOU1000000115_S0000145	the short term debt cycle typically lasts five to eight years and happens over and over again for decades
YOU1000000115_S0000146	but notice that the bottom and top of each cycle finish with more growth than the previous cycle and with more debt
YOU1000000115_S0000147	why because people push it
YOU1000000115_S0000148	they have an inclination to borrow and spend more instead of paying back debt it's human nature
YOU1000000115_S0000149	because of this over long periods of time debts rise faster than incomes creating the long term debt cycle
YOU1000000115_S0000151	despite people becoming more indebted lenders even more freely extend credit
YOU1000000115_S0000153	why
YOU1000000115_S0000155	because everyone thinks things are going great people are just focused on what's been happening lately and what's been happening lately
YOU1000000115_S0000157	incomes have been rising asset values are going up the stock market roars it's a boom
YOU1000000115_S0000158	it pays to buy goods services and financial assets with borrowed money when people do a lot of that we call it a bubble
YOU1000000115_S0000159	so even though debts have been growing incomes have been growing nearly as fast to offset them let's call the ratio of debt to income the debt burden
YOU1000000115_S0000160	so long as incomes continue to rise the debt burden stays manageable at the same time asset values soar
YOU1000000115_S0000161	people borrow huge amounts of money to buy assets as investments causing their prices to rise even higher
YOU1000000115_S0000162	people feel wealthy
YOU1000000115_S0000164	so even with the accumulation of lots of debt rising incomes and asset values help borrowers remain credit-worthy for a long time
YOU1000000115_S0000165	but this obviously can not continue forever and it doesn't
YOU1000000115_S0000166	over decades debt burden slowly increase creating larger and larger debt repayments
YOU1000000115_S0000167	at some point debt repayments start growing faster than incomes forcing people to cut back on their spending
YOU1000000115_S0000168	and since one person's spending is another person's income incomes begin to go down which makes people less creditworthy
YOU1000000115_S0000170	causing borrowing to go down debt repayments continue to rise which makes spending drop even further
YOU1000000115_S0000171	and the cycle reverses itself
YOU1000000115_S0000173	this is the long term debt peak debt burdens have simply become too big
YOU1000000115_S0000175	for the united states europe and much of the rest of the world this happened in two thousand and eight
YOU1000000115_S0000176	it happened for the same reason it happened in japan in nineteen eighty-nine and in the united states back in nineteen twenty-nine
YOU1000000115_S0000177	now the economy begins the leveraging
YOU1000000115_S0000179	in a deleveraging people cut spending incomes fall credit disappears asset prices drop
YOU1000000115_S0000180	banks gets squeezed the stock market crashes social tensions rise and the whole thing starts to feed on itself the other way
YOU1000000115_S0000182	as incomes fall and debt repayments rise borrowers get squeezed no longer credit-worthy
YOU1000000115_S0000183	credit dries up and borrowers can no longer borrow enough money to make their debt repayments
YOU1000000115_S0000184	scrambling to fill this hole borrowers are forced to sell assets the rush to sell assets floods the market at the same time as spending falls
YOU1000000115_S0000185	this is when the stock market collapses the real estate market tanks and banks get into trouble
YOU1000000115_S0000186	as asset prices drop the value of the collateral borrowers can put up drops this makes borrowers even less creditworthy
YOU1000000115_S0000187	people feel poor credit rapidly disappears
YOU1000000115_S0000188	less spending less income less wealth less credit less borrowing and so on it's a vicious cycle
YOU1000000115_S0000189	this appears similar to a recession but the difference here is that interest rates can't be lowered to save the day
YOU1000000115_S0000190	in a recession lowering interest rates works to stimulate borrowing
YOU1000000115_S0000191	however in a deleveraging lowering interest rates doesn't work because interest rates are already low and soon hit zero percent so the stimulation ends
YOU1000000115_S0000193	interest rates in the united states hits zero percent during the deleveraging of the nineteen-thirties and again in two thousand and eight
YOU1000000115_S0000194	the difference between a recession and a deleveraging
YOU1000000115_S0000195	is that in a deleveraging borrowers debt burdens have simply gotten too big and can't be relieved by lowering interest rates
YOU1000000115_S0000196	lenders realize that debts have become too large to ever be fully paid back
YOU1000000115_S0000197	borrowers have lost their ability to repay and their collateral has lost value
YOU1000000115_S0000198	they feel crippled by the debt they don't even want more lenders stop lending borrowers stop borrowing
YOU1000000115_S0000199	think of the economy as being not credit-worthy just like an individual so what do you do about a deleveraging
YOU1000000115_S0000200	the problem is debt burdens are too high and they must come down
YOU1000000115_S0000201	there are four ways this can happen one people businesses and governments cut their spending
YOU1000000115_S0000202	two debts are reduced through defaults and restructurings three wealth is redistributed from the haves to the have nots
YOU1000000115_S0000203	and finally four the central bank prints new money these four ways have happened in every deleveraging in modern history
YOU1000000115_S0000205	usually spending is cut first as we just saw a people businesses and even governments tighten their belts and cut their spending so that they can pay down their debt
YOU1000000115_S0000206	this is often referred to as austerity when borrowers stop taking on new debts and start paying down the old debts
YOU1000000115_S0000207	you might expect the debt burden to decrease but the opposite happens because spending is cut
YOU1000000115_S0000208	and one man's spending is another man's income it causes incomes to fall
YOU1000000115_S0000209	they fall faster than debts are repaid and the debt burden actually gets worse as we've seen this cut in spending is deflationary and painful
YOU1000000115_S0000210	businesses are forced to cut costs which means less jobs and higher unemployment this leads to the next step debts must be reduced
YOU1000000115_S0000211	many borrowers find themselves unable to repay their loans and a borrower's debts are a lender's assets
YOU1000000115_S0000212	when a borrower doesn't repay the bank people get nervous that the bank won't be able to repay them so they rush to withdraw their money from the bank
YOU1000000115_S0000213	banks gets squeezed and people businesses and banks default on their debts
YOU1000000115_S0000214	this severe economic contraction is a depression
YOU1000000115_S0000215	a big part of a depression is people discovering much of what they thought was their wealth isn't really there
YOU1000000115_S0000216	let's go back to the bar when you bought a beer and put it on a bar tab you promised to repay the bartender
YOU1000000115_S0000217	your promise became an asset of the bartender
YOU1000000115_S0000218	but if you break your promise if you don't pay him back and essentially default on your bar tab then the asset he has isn't really worth anything
YOU1000000115_S0000219	it has basically disappeared
YOU1000000115_S0000221	many lenders don't want their assets to disappear and agree to debt restructuring
YOU1000000115_S0000222	debt restructuring means lenders get paid back less or get paid back over a longer time frame or at a lower interest rate than was first agreed
YOU1000000115_S0000223	somehow a contract is broken in a way that reduces debt lenders would rather have a little of something than all of nothing
YOU1000000115_S0000224	even though debt disappears debt restructuring causes income and asset values to disappear faster so the debt burden continues to get worse
YOU1000000115_S0000225	like cutting spending debt reduction is also painful and deflationary
YOU1000000115_S0000227	all of this impacts the central government because lower incomes and less employment means the government collects fewer taxes
YOU1000000115_S0000228	at the same time it needs to increase its spending because unemployment has risen
YOU1000000115_S0000229	many of the unemployed have inadequate savings and need financial support from the government
YOU1000000115_S0000230	additionally governments create stimulus plans and increase their spending to make up for the decrease in the economy
YOU1000000115_S0000231	government's budget deficits explode in a deleveraging because they spend more than they earn in taxes
YOU1000000115_S0000232	this is what's happening when you hear about the budget deficit on the news
YOU1000000115_S0000234	to fund their deficits governments need to either raise taxes or borrow money
YOU1000000115_S0000235	but with incomes falling and so many unemployed who is the money going come from
YOU1000000115_S0000236	the rich since governments need more money and since wealth is heavily concentrated in the hands of a small percentage of the people
YOU1000000115_S0000237	governments naturally raise taxes on the wealthy which facilitates a redistribution of wealth in the economy from the haves to the have-nots
YOU1000000115_S0000238	the have-nots who were suffering begin to resent the wealthy haves
YOU1000000115_S0000239	the wealthy haves being squeezed by the weak economy falling asset prices and higher taxes begin to resent the have-nots
YOU1000000115_S0000240	if the depression continues social disorder can break out
YOU1000000115_S0000241	not only detentions rise within countries they can rise between countries especially debtor and creditor countries
YOU1000000115_S0000242	this situation can lead to political change that can sometimes be extreme
YOU1000000115_S0000243	in the nineteen-thirties this led to hitler coming to power war in europe and depression in the united states
YOU1000000115_S0000244	pressure to do something to end the depression increases
YOU1000000115_S0000245	remember most of what people thought was money was actually credit so when credit disappears people don't have enough money
YOU1000000115_S0000246	people are desperate for money and you remember who can print money the central bank can
YOU1000000115_S0000248	having already lowered its interest rates to nearly zero it's forced to print money
YOU1000000115_S0000249	unlike cutting spending debt reduction and wealth redistribution printing money is inflationary and stimulative
YOU1000000115_S0000250	inevitably the central bank prints new money out of thin air and uses it to buy financial assets and government bonds
YOU1000000115_S0000251	it happened in the united states during the great depression
YOU1000000115_S0000252	and again in two thousand and eight when the united states central bank the federal reserve printed over two trillion dollars
YOU1000000115_S0000253	other central banks around the world that could printed a lot of money too
YOU1000000115_S0000254	by buying financial assets with this money it helps drive up asset prices which makes people more credit-worthy
YOU1000000115_S0000255	however this only helps those who own financial assets you see the central bank can print money but it can only buy financial assets
YOU1000000115_S0000256	the central government on the other hand can buy goods and services and put money in the hands of the people but it can't print money
YOU1000000115_S0000257	so in order to stimulate the economy the two must cooperate
YOU1000000115_S0000258	by buying government bonds the central bank essentially lends money to the government allowing it to run a deficit and increase spending
YOU1000000115_S0000259	on goods and services through it's stimulus programs and on employment benefits
YOU1000000115_S0000260	this increases people's income as well as the government's debt however it will lower the economy's total debt burden
YOU1000000115_S0000261	this is a very risky time policy makers need to balance the four ways that debt burdens come down
YOU1000000115_S0000263	the deflationary ways need to balance with the inflationary ways in order to maintain stability
YOU1000000115_S0000264	if balanced correctly there can be a beautiful deleveraging
YOU1000000115_S0000266	you see a deleveraging could be ugly or it can be beautiful how can a deleveraging be beautiful
YOU1000000115_S0000268	even though a deleveraging is a difficult situation handling a difficult situation in the best possible way is beautiful
YOU1000000115_S0000269	a lot more beautiful than the debt fueled unbalanced excesses of the leveraging phase
YOU1000000115_S0000270	in a beautiful deleveraging debts decline relative to income real economic growth is positive and inflation isn't a problem
YOU1000000115_S0000271	it is achieved by having the right balance the right balance requires a certain mix of cutting spending reducing debt
YOU1000000115_S0000273	transferring wealth and printing money so that economic and social stability can be maintained
YOU1000000115_S0000274	people ask if printing money will raise inflation it won't if it offsets fall in credit
YOU1000000115_S0000275	remember spending is what matters a dollar of spending paid for with money has the same effect on prices a dollar of spending paid for with credit
YOU1000000115_S0000277	by printing money the central bank can make up for the disappearance of credit with an increase in the amount of money
YOU1000000115_S0000278	in order to turn things around the central bank needs to not only pump up income growth
YOU1000000115_S0000279	but get the rate of income growth higher than the rate of interest on the accumulated debt
YOU1000000115_S0000280	so what do i mean by that basically income needs to grow faster than debt grows
YOU1000000115_S0000281	for example let's assume that a country going through a deleveraging has a debt to income ratio of a hundred percent
YOU1000000115_S0000282	that means that the amount of debt it has is the same as the amount of income the entire country makes in a year
YOU1000000115_S0000283	now think about the interest rate on that debt let's say it's two percent
YOU1000000115_S0000284	if debt is growing at two percent because of that interest rate and income is only growing at around one percent you will never reduce the debt burden
YOU1000000115_S0000285	you need to print enough money to get the rate of income growth above the rate of interest
YOU1000000115_S0000286	however printing money could easily be abused because it's so easy to do and people prefer it to the alternatives
YOU1000000115_S0000287	the key is to avoid printing too much money and causing unacceptably high inflation the way germany did during it's deleveraging in the nineteen-twenties
YOU1000000115_S0000288	if policy makers achieve the right balance a deleveraging isn't so dramatic growth is slow but debt burdens go down
YOU1000000115_S0000289	that's a beautiful deleveraging when incomes begin to rise borrowers begin to appear more credit-worthy
YOU1000000115_S0000290	and when borrowers appear more credit-worthy lenders begin to lend money again debt burdens finally begin to fall
YOU1000000115_S0000291	able to borrow money people can spend more eventually the economy begins to grow again leading to the reflation phase of the long-term debt cycle
YOU1000000115_S0000292	though the deleveraging process can be horrible if handled badly if handled well it will eventually fix the problem
YOU1000000115_S0000293	it takes roughly a decade or more for debt burdens to fall and economic activity to get back to normal hence the term lost decade
YOU1000000115_S0000294	enclosing of course the economy is a little bit more complicated than this template suggests
YOU1000000115_S0000295	however laying the short-term debt cycle on top of the long-term debt cycle and then laying both of them on top of the productivity growth line
YOU1000000115_S0000296	gives a reasonably good template for seeing where we've been where we are now and where we're probably headed
YOU1000000115_S0000297	so in summary there are three rules of thumb that i'd like you to take away from this
YOU1000000115_S0000298	first don't have debt rise faster than income because your debt burdens will eventually crush you
YOU1000000115_S0000299	second don't have income rise faster than productivity because you'll eventually become uncompetitive
YOU1000000115_S0000300	and third do all that you can to raise your productivity because in the long run that's what matters most
YOU1000000115_S0000301	this is simple advice for you and it's simple advice for policy makers
YOU1000000115_S0000302	you might be surprised but most people including most policy makers don't pay enough attention to this
YOU1000000115_S0000303	this template has worked for me and i hope it will work for you thank you
