YOU1000000130_S0000005	by all accounts henry ford should've been a farmer born in michigan barely twenty years after it had become a state
YOU1000000130_S0000006	henry grew up at a time when farming was slow exhausting and manual which is why unsurprisingly he came to hate it with a passion but whereas most people at the time didn't have the fortune to escape what they were born into
YOU1000000130_S0000007	henry was lucky enough to get such an opportunity you see the village he was born in was just eight miles west of detroit which was rapidly becoming an industrial center thanks to the steam engine
YOU1000000130_S0000008	early on in his childhood henry encountered technology which few children his age could play around with
YOU1000000130_S0000009	he'd tinker with the watches of his better-off neighbors and by the time he was twelve he could not just take them apart but also put them back together and repair them
YOU1000000130_S0000010	his interest grew into an obsession when he got to observe a working steam engine firsthand while on a school trip to one of the rail companies in detroit
YOU1000000130_S0000011	by the time henry had become a teenager the steam engine was already making its way into the farming community coal-powered threshing machines and sawmills were becoming common sight and henry was learning how they worked and how to fix them
YOU1000000130_S0000012	at the age of sixteen he made a big leap forward when against his father's wishes he left his village to go work in detroit where any young mechanic could easily find very lucrative employment
YOU1000000130_S0000013	industry in detroit was booming and it had been doing so for close to five decades in eighteen twenty-five a canal had been dug connecting the hudson river to the great lakes which at the time were effectively the western frontier
YOU1000000130_S0000014	all the untapped resources that had not way of getting out could suddenly be moved by steamboat to new york and in the span of just fifty years detroit's population increased by a factor of ten
YOU1000000130_S0000015	with vast mines in the north producing copper and iron and lumber mills opening up virtually everywhere
YOU1000000130_S0000016	all this metal and wood sustained close to a thousand companies in detroit alone including the ones in which henry would work at over the course of the eighteen eighties
YOU1000000130_S0000017	it is during this time that henry by chance learned about the gas engine from a british magazine it was being produced in small numbers by a german engineer nikolaus otto
YOU1000000130_S0000018	and it was gaining some traction in europe but it was practically unheard of in america henry would get the chance to work on suchan engine himself in eighteen eighty-nine and he instantly recognized the advantages it had
YOU1000000130_S0000019	because it did not use steam the engine was much lighter it got rid of the heavy boiler and all the water in it because it did all the combustion internally a much more efficient process
YOU1000000130_S0000020	this also allowed the gas engine to start quickly whereas steam engines of the time needed as much as thirty minutes to heat up the water and generate enough steam to start working the gas engine was an innovation henry fell in love with
YOU1000000130_S0000021	but it was one he didn't fully understand after all he had extensive experience with steam and metal but almost none with electricity and the gas engine was fired by an electric spark
YOU1000000130_S0000022	to obtain this missing knowledge henry went to work for the local branch of the edison illuminating company
YOU1000000130_S0000023	it was generating electricity for over a thousand homes in detroit and it was doing so by using steam engines so henry was a natural hire for them whenever the engines broke henry had to fix them but whenever they were working
YOU1000000130_S0000024	he was free to do as he wished it was the perfect job that allowed him to spend his days experimenting with gas engines in eighteen ninety-three when henry had already been promoted to chief engineer at edison
YOU1000000130_S0000025	he created his first working gas engine the idea of using the gas engine to create a horseless carriage had been around in henry's mind since he first laid eyes on one but actually making that idea a reality would take years of work
YOU1000000130_S0000026	building a car in a world with no car parts wasn't easy and henry had to figure out every detail through trial and error it took him three years of constant effort to produce this the quadricycle
YOU1000000130_S0000027	a simple frame with an engine powered by ethanol and four bicycle wheels mounted onto it it had only two gears and neither one was for going in reverse but what's worse is that it had no cooling system to speak of
YOU1000000130_S0000028	thus making overheating a constant issue in its first year henry made numerous improvements to the quadricycle most notably adding a cooling system and by the time he sold it in eighteen ninety-seven for two hundred dollars
YOU1000000130_S0000029	he had driven a thousand miles in it henry built a second quadricycle and then a third one always improving the design before finally feeling confident enough in eighteen ninety-nine to start his own company
YOU1000000130_S0000031	capitalized at a hundred and fifty thousand dollars the detroit automobile company was a very ambitious venture many of the detroit elite invested in it including henry's friends from the edison company
YOU1000000130_S0000032	and everyone was eager to see what henry could create with proper capital henry's plan was very clever since he personally knew many of the industrialists in detroit by that point he'd try to build an automobile they could use in their businesses
YOU1000000130_S0000033	he leased a factory and planned to hire a hundred workers to make his new delivery wagon as he called it but it turned out that building such complex machines in high numbers was much more difficult than henry imagined
YOU1000000130_S0000034	the vast majority of the parts used in the making of the delivery wagon were produced by other companies and every time a single delivery was late the entire factory would have no choice but to stop working
YOU1000000130_S0000035	the first delivery wagon took six months to produce and no more than twenty were made in the first two years of the company's existence by the end of nineteen o two the other shareholders were sick of henry's lack of progress
YOU1000000130_S0000036	and actually voted to get rid of him now because henry held only fifteen percent of the company he had no choice but to comply
YOU1000000130_S0000037	and interestingly enough the man who took over the detroit automobile company would eventually transform it into cadillac but that's a story for a different time what matters is that henry was pushed out of his own company
YOU1000000130_S0000038	and had only a thousand dollars to his name it was back to the drawing board and this time henry would take a very different approach instead of targeting businesses with expensive machines henry would design a vehicle to be used by the average man
YOU1000000130_S0000039	you see at the time virtually all cars were high-ticket items they were mostly made by skilled craftsmen one at a time and more often than not were designed for racing which was rapidly becoming a favorite american activity
YOU1000000130_S0000040	henry envisioned turning the car from a status symbol into a commodity but doing that would not be easy and in fact it took henry twenty different design iterations before he finally got one that worked
YOU1000000130_S0000041	henry labeled his first design as the model a and worked his way through the alphabet over the next five years sustained by capital from his friends and family
YOU1000000130_S0000042	but what changed the most during this time is not the car itself but the production process henry learned the importance of having a reliable supply chain when his first company failed which is why this time around
YOU1000000130_S0000043	he tried getting as many parts as possible from the same manufacturer the one he chose will probably sound familiar the dodge brothers company a machine shop in detroit that would eventually evolve into the eponymous american brand
YOU1000000130_S0000044	the biggest game-changer of all however was henry's chance visit to a slaughterhouse in chicago he saw there something interesting a disassembly line so to speak where multiple workers would process carcasses moving down a line
YOU1000000130_S0000045	henry figured he could use the same process but in reverse an assembly line using the money he had saved from some of his earlier models which were also assembled by the dodge brothers
YOU1000000130_S0000046	henry was able to build a factory of his own in nineteen o four where he could experiment with the assembly line process by nineteen o five the ford factory employed over three hundred people that built twenty-five cars a day
YOU1000000130_S0000047	but henry still hadn't figured everything out he was producing multiple different models at the same time which prevented him from properly using an assembly line
YOU1000000130_S0000048	nevertheless there was a sign of things to come the affordable model n created in nineteen o six became the best-selling car in the u s and ford became the biggest car producer in america
YOU1000000130_S0000049	it is actually during the production of this model that henry would first use the assembly line process to at least partially assemble some of his cars
YOU1000000130_S0000050	it wasn't a full moving assembly line but nevertheless this experiment increased production by a factor of five in the same factory logistics of course was another big part of henry's success
YOU1000000130_S0000051	in nineteen o five he created the ford manufacturing company completed with its own factory that started making the engines and transmissions of henry's cars to further eliminate any possibility of delays
YOU1000000130_S0000052	but the biggest factor in henry's success came from perhaps the most unexpected place peru now this is a story you're not gonna hear anywhere else so listen carefully
YOU1000000130_S0000053	in nineteen o seven henry began construction of heat treatment plant to produce vanadium steel
YOU1000000130_S0000054	this alloy was new to america in fact few furnaces in the u s could even reach the temperature needed to manufacture it the difficulty in producing it however was worth it
YOU1000000130_S0000055	because vanadium steel was more than twice as strong as regular steel while actually being lighter now at the time vanadium metallurgy was cutting edge research
YOU1000000130_S0000056	but henry had an extremely lucky connection he was friends with the two brothers who owned the one vanadium mine in peru producing ninety-two percent of the world's supply
YOU1000000130_S0000057	joseph and james flannery had commercialized vanadium steel in europe and in the u s by selling it to rail companies but their peruvian mine was producing so much vanadium that they had to do something else with it
YOU1000000130_S0000059	they sold vanadium steel to the u s government for the construction of the panama canal but even that wasn't enough so when they met henry in nineteen o six they immediately made him an offer
YOU1000000130_S0000060	they would help him transition his entire manufacturing process to use vanadium steel it was their chief engineer that built the heat treatment plant for henry in nineteen o seven
YOU1000000130_S0000061	and it was their company that supplied ford with all the vanadium it needed for its cars the first ford car designed with vanadium steel was the model t in nineteen o eight and it was this alloy that actually made it successful
YOU1000000130_S0000062	it wasn't the cheapest car henry had made the model n and its upscale versions were actually cheaper but it didn't need to be because it was by far the best car built at the time much stronger than any competitor
YOU1000000130_S0000063	the sheer difference in quality was the only marketing henry needed and within weeks of the model t released ford received twenty-five thousand orders for it
YOU1000000130_S0000064	even though it only managed to produce seventeen thousand units for the entirety of nineteen o nine henry realized just how big of a deal the model t was which is why he built a second factory in nineteen ten
YOU1000000130_S0000065	and it is there that he would perfect the moving assembly line in nineteen thirteen during this period production would double every year in nineteen ten he built twenty thousand model ts
YOU1000000130_S0000066	and just six year later he was building over half a million at the same time henry adopted another brilliant strategy he was constantly reducing the price of his car to further increase his market share
YOU1000000130_S0000067	in fact during these six years he cut the model t's price by more than half by nineteen eighteen half of all cars in america were model ts and this trend would continue well into the nineteen twenties
YOU1000000130_S0000068	henry had begun a new age in american history the age of the automobile and it was his company that would totally dominate in its first two decades
YOU1000000130_S0000069	it wasn't until the end of the nineteen twenties that the rest of the auto industry caught up to henry but at that point he was already one of the richest men alive
