YOU1000000131_S0000000	when you look at the wealthiest men alive today topping the charts are tech billionaires like jeff bezos and bill gates but actually the wealthiest businessman to have ever lived died almost a century ago
YOU1000000131_S0000001	in today's video we'll be looking at a business empire so vast that even after a hundred years of technological progress no man has managed to overtake its founder this is the history of standard oil
YOU1000000131_S0000003	this video was brought to you by dollar shave club visit the link in the description to learn about the awesome deal they're offering
YOU1000000131_S0000005	the origins of history's greatest oil monopoly are actually pretty humble it all starts in eighteen thirty-nine with the birth of john rockefeller in upstate new york he was the eldest son of a travelling merchant
YOU1000000131_S0000006	who identified himself as a botanic physician but in reality was selling the nineteenth century equivalent of homeopathic medicine
YOU1000000131_S0000007	he would spend weeks away from home and in fact would have several children with another woman who he decided to bring back home to his wife
YOU1000000131_S0000008	so they could all live together in this very confusing household john would grow up learning how to hustle people for the best deal possible and how to get the most out of every penny he got his family would rarely stay in one place for long
YOU1000000131_S0000009	and john would live this nomadic lifestyle ever since he was three years old to help his mother john would earn any money he could by raising turkeys or doing work for neighbors his intelligence was put to good use
YOU1000000131_S0000010	when the family moved to cleveland ohio in eighteen fifty-four where he got the chance to attend a proper school but less than a year later john dropped out in order to work as a bookkeeper at a local produce broker he would earn fifty cents per day
YOU1000000131_S0000011	which obviously wasn't much at the time so he would help other companies on the side but after two years of working there his bosses refused to give him a meaningful raise so he decided to one up them by starting his own produce brokerage
YOU1000000131_S0000012	thanks to his good reputation he got a loan of four thousand dollars which at the time was a huge sum john started trading hay grain and various meats and in his first year he recorded sales of half a million dollars
YOU1000000131_S0000013	of which he only got a small fraction as commissions but still it was a huge success every bank in cleveland was begging john to borrow money and he was barely eighteen years old but then in eighteen fifty-nine
YOU1000000131_S0000014	something happened that would change his life forever just a hundred miles east of cleveland the first american oil well had been discovered this marked the beginning of the pennsylvania oil rush and within a year
YOU1000000131_S0000015	four and half thousand barrels of oil would be produced now back then oil wasn't quite as valuable as it today gasoline cars hadn't been invented yet but oil could still be processed into kerosene which people would then use in lamps
YOU1000000131_S0000016	john realized however that the biggest profits to be had weren't in drilling for oil but in refining it he witnessed many people going bust before striking oil so he knew that that business was too risky for him
YOU1000000131_S0000017	instead he'd let others go through the hassle of finding the oil and he would just buy it off of them john had to wait until eighteen sixty-three for the government to build a rail line connecting the pennsylvania oil fields to cleveland
YOU1000000131_S0000018	but when that line was built john was ready for it with a long line of partners and banks ready to back him up he also assembled a team of seasoned chemists and engineers who not only optimized the refining process but also discovered various uses
YOU1000000131_S0000019	for the byproducts of refining petroleum you see the early refineries in cleveland could only operate at about sixty percent efficiency but john not only increased that percentage he also started selling all the byproducts like paraffin wax
YOU1000000131_S0000020	tar and naphtha within two years the rockefeller refinery was worth over seventy thousand dollars and was among the largest in cleveland but john wasn't done
YOU1000000131_S0000021	in eighteen sixty-five there were twenty-six competing refineries but within five years john had acquired all but four of them
YOU1000000131_S0000023	by this point his business was getting too big to handle as a partnership so in eighteen seventy he incorporated as standard oil of ohio to convince the few remaining competitors in cleveland john would simply invite them over and show them his books
YOU1000000131_S0000024	revealing that he could operate at a loss far longer than they could stay solvent in exchange for a good buyout price john would offer his competitors positions in his own company thus placing the brightest minds in the industry under his control
YOU1000000131_S0000025	of course not everyone would give up immediately and over time john eroded the price of oil and kerosene sometimes by as much as eighty percent in order to strangle competitors unsurprisingly his strategy worked
YOU1000000131_S0000026	by eighteen eighty he had acquired refineries across the northeastern u s and was refining over ninety percent of the entire country's oil production at this point john was so powerful that he would invite the owners of the big rail companies
YOU1000000131_S0000027	and personally negotiate rebates for using their trains but this practice of negotiating backroom deals really got the business world riled up at the time and still kind of today most industrial goods were transported by rail
YOU1000000131_S0000028	and many big industrialists got worried
YOU1000000131_S0000030	that john's abuse of transportation rebates could result in similar monopolization in their industries
YOU1000000131_S0000031	over the next decade businessmen politicians and the media would attack standard oil with increasing ferocity legislators in ohio began drafting antitrust regulations to bring down rockefeller but he was one step ahead
YOU1000000131_S0000032	in eighteen eighty-two he reincorporated in new jersey this time creating the standard oil trust which in turn held stakes in over forty local companies
YOU1000000131_S0000033	then to showcase his success john built an impressive headquarters for his company on broadway this moment was the high point of rockefeller's standard oil
YOU1000000131_S0000034	he owned twenty thousand oil wells four thousand miles of pipeline and employed over a hundred thousand people but his grip on the oil industry was loosening both domestically and abroad
YOU1000000131_S0000035	massive oil deposits had been discovered in russia and in asia and were being developed by the rothschild family which spared no effort in getting that oil to america
YOU1000000131_S0000036	worse yet in eighteen ninety the federal government passed the sherman antitrust act which finally gave politicians the teeth to go after the standard oil trust itself
YOU1000000131_S0000037	of course the complex legal structure behind all the companies was very difficult to investigate which is why it the government couldn't actually break up standard oil until nineteen eleven
YOU1000000131_S0000038	by that point however john rockefeller had already cashed in and was no longer actively managing the company in the final twenty years of his company's existence it had paid out over half a billion dollars in dividends
YOU1000000131_S0000039	by some estimates the true worth of standard oil at its peak was one trillion dollars so the breakup didn't really come as a surprise to most people in nineteen eleven the supreme court found standard oil guilty of anticompetitive practices
YOU1000000131_S0000040	and broke the company up into thirty-four separate entities of course john rockefeller kept his stake in those companies until his death and in fact it turns out that the breakup was the most profitable event in his life
YOU1000000131_S0000041	you see over time many of those companies merged back with one another today most of the standard remnants are part of either exxonmobil chevron or b p which have since become incredibly large companies in their own right
YOU1000000131_S0000042	john rockefeller's ownership of these successor companies made him the richest businessman to have ever lived with an estimated net worth of four hundred billion dollars even today no one has beaten rockefeller in the leaderboard
YOU1000000131_S0000043	not even jeff bezos himself seems likely to achieve that but there's one thing that jeff bezos does have that john rockefeller never did despite all his money and that is access to dollar shave club
