YOU1000000133_S0000000	the internet has completely changed the way we watch television goner the days when the whole family would gather in the living room to enjoy the exact same program as everyone else
YOU1000000133_S0000001	technology has advanced to the point where we've dumped the old immovable boxes in favor of our phones and computers in today's world you can watch whatever you want whenever you want on-demand straight from the internet
YOU1000000133_S0000002	we are now in the age of video-on-demand and so this week on behind the business we'll be taking a look at the company that lies at the heart of this recent revolution netflix
YOU1000000133_S0000004	the year is nineteen ninety-one and reed hastings was getting ready to start his first company hastings was a rather unusual tech entrepreneur
YOU1000000133_S0000005	he came from minnesota and after graduating from college and serving briefly in the military he decided to travel to swaziland with the peace corps to teach math
YOU1000000133_S0000006	after returning to the u s and getting a masters in computer science he and two of his friends started a company in nineteen ninety-one called pure software as the company sold a range of debugging tools for unix operating systems at a time when there were few good ones on the market
YOU1000000133_S0000007	and so it rapidly became a big player in the i t world it doubled its revenue every year for four years in a row and in nineteen ninety-six it was sold to rational software for seven hundred million dollars
YOU1000000133_S0000008	in the span of half a decade hastings had become a millionaire
YOU1000000133_S0000009	life seemed great but in nineteen ninety-seven he suffered an inconvenience that would eventually become a world-changer hastings had forgotten to return his video-rental of apollo thirteen and as a result was slapped with a forty dollar late fee
YOU1000000133_S0000010	he was embarrassed and didn't want to tell his wife and that got him to thinking of a solution not just a solution to his own late-fee problem but a solution to everyone's problem an entirely new system of film rental that would make late fees obsolete
YOU1000000133_S0000011	together with a friend of his on august twenty-ninth nineteen ninety-seven in scotts valley california hastings founded a brand new movie rental service called netflix with the idea of mailing d v ds to paying customers
YOU1000000133_S0000012	the creation of netflix was essentially a bet on the d v d player now the d v d player had been invented in taiwan in nineteen ninety-four by sony but it wouldn't be until march nineteen ninety-seven that one was first sold in the u s
YOU1000000133_S0000013	back then a player cost over a thousand dollars and when netflix was formed less than one percent of americans actually owned one
YOU1000000133_S0000014	in a move that seemed insane at the time hastings gambled everything on the potential of d v d technology to replace the bulkier lower-resolution videotape as the nation's format of choice
YOU1000000133_S0000015	in nineteen ninety-seven it was almost impossible for people to rent d v ds because very few places had any
YOU1000000133_S0000016	after trying over two hundred different mailing packages and testing them out by mailing them to himself hastings discovered that he could safely ship a d v d for the small cost of a first-class mail stamp
YOU1000000133_S0000017	this way netflix could guarantee that most titles would be in stock and by enclosing a stamped return mailer they could make the experience of film-rental as convenient as possible
YOU1000000133_S0000018	thus on april fourteen nineteen ninety-eight with thirty employees and an assortment of nine hundred twenty-five titles netflix opened for business
YOU1000000133_S0000019	their first offer was for a seven day rental at the price of four dollars plus a two dollar shipping fee they also introduced something that is now one of netflix's proudest hallmark smart suggestion algorithms
YOU1000000133_S0000020	once a customer had rented enough titles netflix could automatically suggest new movies that were likely to interest them nowadays when google and facebook know everything about us it's easy to take such algorithms for granted but in nineteen ninety-seven they were practically unheard of
YOU1000000133_S0000021	netflix started strong and just forty-eight hours after opening they had to upgrade their website's bandwidth due to excessive traffic they were receiving
YOU1000000133_S0000022	soon netflix signed promotional deals with toshiba hewlett-packard and sony whereby they offered free rentals to people who bought new d v d players
YOU1000000133_S0000023	in july nineteen ninety-nine netflix secured a thirty million dollar capital injections from groupe arnault which allowed them to start a subscription-based service called the marquee program
YOU1000000133_S0000024	for just under sixteen dollars per month customers could rent out as many d v ds as they wanted as long as they had no more than four d v ds at any given time no late fees no due dates it was perfect
YOU1000000133_S0000025	by that point netflix was already receiving ten thousand d v d orders every day but their total revenue was sitting at barely five million dollars compare this to blockbuster's four point five billion dollar revenue and you'll probably see why netflix decided to try to team up with them
YOU1000000133_S0000026	blockbuster was one of the oldest video rental companies and it was by far the largest with sixty thousand employees and eight thousand stores spread across the u s
YOU1000000133_S0000027	as the popularity of netflix grew everyone thought blockbuster would soon enter the market and with their vast resources they would've probably crushed their young competitor
YOU1000000133_S0000028	that is why netflix decided to act first and so in the early year two thousand they invited blockbuster to become a strategic partner and investor
YOU1000000133_S0000029	netflix would become the internet arm of the blockbuster brand dropping the netflix name altogether in favor of blockbuster dot com
YOU1000000133_S0000030	blockbuster laughed them out of the boardroom they were certain netflix would crumble as it has yet to turn a profit three years after its creation instead a few months later blockbuster partnered up with enron broadband
YOU1000000133_S0000031	a division of the energy company you probably know today for its notoriously fraudulent accounting practices
YOU1000000133_S0000033	of course at the time nobody knew that and so investors praised blockbuster's decision the situation for netflix looked grim they were losing money fast and by the end of the year they reported a net loss of fifty-seven million dollars
YOU1000000133_S0000034	despite doubts coming from all sides hastings was convinced that d v d technology would prevail the only thing that mattered to him was to simply survive until that happened and two thousand one was the year when things finally started going his way
YOU1000000133_S0000035	the price of d v d players plummeted with some going around for less than a hundred bucks two thousand one also saw the nine eleven terrorist attacks fearful americans took refuge in their homes and netflix subscriptions skyrocketed
YOU1000000133_S0000036	despite growing at an unprecedented rate netflix still hadn't turned a profit and so in two thousand two they went public to keep the company going in two thousand three they crossed the one million subscriber mark and finally had their first profitable year
YOU1000000133_S0000037	just as their fortune started to turn however in two thousand four blockbuster finally released their own online d v d mail service before long walmart also joined the fray and a three way battle to undercut one another ensued
YOU1000000133_S0000038	blockbuster and walmart however were a bit late to the party hastings admitted that if they had started two years earlier they probably would have won on an end of year conference call hastings declared blockbuster has thrown everything but the kitchen sink at us
YOU1000000133_S0000039	when the c e o of blockbuster heard that he promptly had a kitchen sink delivered to the netflix office a fairly creative way of declaring war
YOU1000000133_S0000040	as the competitors undercut one another netflix saw its brief profitability evaporate and its stock fell by seventy-five percent
YOU1000000133_S0000041	despite losing money they kept on growing and by two thousand five netflix was shipping one million d v ds every day from their assortment of over thirty-five thousand titles eventually this drawn-out battle of attrition took its toll
YOU1000000133_S0000042	and in two thousand five walmart decided to quit blockbuster followed suit and as the era of brick-and-mortar video rental came to an end so did their success in two thousand eight the same c e o that had rejected netflix was fired
YOU1000000133_S0000043	and by two thousand ten blockbuster had filed for bankruptcy netflix had emerged victorious and in two thousand seven it celebrated the delivery of its billionth d v d then in a single announcement hastings began the journey of making the very bedrock of his company obsolete
YOU1000000133_S0000044	this was his end-game the reason he had been willing to sacrifice profits for so long and the same reason he had prophetically cited back in the year two thousand video-on-demand
YOU1000000133_S0000046	netflix first started offering streaming of on-demand videos in two thousand seven and initially the service was at no additional charge at first movie rights were hard to come by and the videos available to stream on netflix were well pretty awful
YOU1000000133_S0000047	but in october two thousand eight they signed a deal with premium cable outlet starz which brought in some huge disney and sony library releases the deal cost netflix only twenty million dollars a price that they soon discovered was an absolute bargain
YOU1000000133_S0000048	the reason netflix got such a great price was because they were the only big player in town and pretty soon they signed deals with paramount m g m and lionsgate
YOU1000000133_S0000049	netflix were also pushing for partnerships with other brands and before long they were featured on nearly every major entertainment system on the planet they buddied up with apple playstation xbox nintendo wii and a bunch of other brands
YOU1000000133_S0000050	by two thousand ten nearly thirty percent of all north american broadband traffic during peak hours came from netflix they expanded into canada in two thousand ten latin america and the caribbean in two thousand eleven and europe in two thousand twelve
YOU1000000133_S0000051	two thousand eleven turned out to be a year of huge surprises for netflix in response to the ever increasing cost of content streaming licenses netflix announced the production of their first piece of original content it would be a political drama called house of cards
YOU1000000133_S0000052	featuring kevin spacey and directed by david fincher netflix managed to outbid h b o by ordering the first two seasons upfront for one hundred million dollars in october of that year however netflix made a much less successful move
YOU1000000133_S0000053	they introduced a new service called qwikster which yes is spelled with a w in reality there was nothing new about qwikster at all it was basically the spin-off of netflix's old d v d rental service
YOU1000000133_S0000054	the branding was sloppy unimaginative and just not thought-out but the public's response to qwikster was even worse netflix lost eight hundred thousand subscribers in a single month and three months later their shares had lost two thirds their value
YOU1000000133_S0000055	unsurprisingly they shut qwikster down the very next month bringing the two arms of the business back together the first piece of netflix original content was lilyhammer which aired on february sixth two thousand twelve
YOU1000000133_S0000056	it was a relative success and it paved the way for the bigger shows that were to follow in two thousand thirteen first and foremost was house of cards which first aired on february first and became one of netflix's most acclaimed titles
YOU1000000133_S0000057	airing the entire first season all at once was a bold move by netflix and it revolutionized the way people watch t v shows following the same format came arrested development in may and orange is the new black in july
YOU1000000133_S0000058	netflix continued to use suggestion algorithms to keep people glued to their computers watching series after series each available in its entirety on-demand
YOU1000000133_S0000060	these algorithms have become exponentially smarter in recent years and they can now spot gaps in the market giving netflix an edge in developing new shows
YOU1000000133_S0000061	at this point netflix can create original content based solely on what their customers want before they even know that they want it
YOU1000000133_S0000062	that strategy has worked out marvelously for them so far and in two thousand thirteen netflix received fourteen emmy nominations nine of which were for house of cards
YOU1000000133_S0000063	they continue to create original content from t v series to documentaries to movies though perhaps their faith in adam sandler with whom they are releasing four new movies is somewhat misplaced
YOU1000000133_S0000064	by the end of two thousand sixteen netflix will have released six hundred hours of new original content for the year and they will have spent a whopping six billion dollars on content acquisition this aggressive expansion is the only option they have
