YOU1000000155_S0000000	real estate investing rules of thumb the two percent rule the fifty percent rule and the seventy percent rule
YOU1000000155_S0000001	there are some rules of thumb that can help investors quickly scream through deals to make a good educated guess on whether not to pursue them
YOU1000000155_S0000002	now this is important notice that i didn't say there are some rules of thumb that help investors make purchase decisions
YOU1000000155_S0000003	because rules of thumb are not meant to be hard and fast rules they simply help an investor get a quick and dirty opinion on some valuable metrics
YOU1000000155_S0000004	always do a proper analysis but regardless these rules of thumb can come in really handy in saving you from analyzing every single deal that you've come across
YOU1000000155_S0000005	my name is brenton turner and in this video i've outlined several of the most common real estate map rules of thumb
YOU1000000155_S0000006	so you can begin practicing them in your own analysis of properties
YOU1000000155_S0000008	first the two percent rule also known as the one percent rule or the two percent test
YOU1000000155_S0000009	perhaps one of the most common rules of thumb used by rental property investors is known as the two percent rule
YOU1000000155_S0000010	but not because it's a rule so i say two percent test i like that better
YOU1000000155_S0000011	essentially this rule of thumb looks at the monthly rent divided by the value of the property in a percentage form
YOU1000000155_S0000012	for those who just got confused let's make this super simple if a property rents for two thousand dollars a month
YOU1000000155_S0000013	and the value is two hundred thousand dollars and in two thousand divided by two hundred thousand equals one percent
YOU1000000155_S0000014	in this example the property does not pass the two percent test but it doesn't meet the one percent test exactly
YOU1000000155_S0000015	or what if the property it rents for fifteen hundred hundred a month and it costs a hundred and eighty thousand to buy well fifteen hundred divided by a hundred eight thousand is point eight percent
YOU1000000155_S0000016	that's definitely short of the one percent rule or one percent test now what if that property rents for fifteen hundred a month but it's worth a hundred and twenty thousand
YOU1000000155_S0000017	well fifteen hundred divided by a hundred twenty thousand equals one point two five percent all right so you get how that works now right but what does it mean
YOU1000000155_S0000018	well essentially the one percent or two percent test gives us a quick and dirty view on whether or not the property will produce positive cash flow
YOU1000000155_S0000019	and of course just a rule of thumb it isn't always precise but generally speaking the higher the percentage the better the cash flow
YOU1000000155_S0000020	this is also greatly depends on location price and how much the expenses truly are on the property
YOU1000000155_S0000021	but the rule of thumb can help an investor make some decisions on whether or not to pursue a certain property
YOU1000000155_S0000022	for example i know that most properties that fall short of one percent will likely never produce a positive cash flow for me
YOU1000000155_S0000023	if it's one and two percent it probably will and if it's above two percent which is really hard to find today then i'm almost positive that it will
YOU1000000155_S0000024	so if my real estate agent tells me that they have a perfect rental house for me to buy and i see that the purchase price is a hundred and twenty-five thousand
YOU1000000155_S0000025	and i find that old rent for a thousand dollars a month i can make a very quick decision and i know that most likely ideal ain't gonna ever provide cash flow
YOU1000000155_S0000026	because it falls short of the one percent rule because a thousand divided by a hundred twenty-five equals point eight percent
YOU1000000155_S0000027	in a case like this i probably wouldn't spend any more time looking at the deal if i was only interested in the cash flow
YOU1000000155_S0000028	so that's the value of the two percent rule test thing while the two percent rule and the one percent rule or test we just mentioned
YOU1000000155_S0000029	they can help you get with a like go no go decision on looking further into a rental property
YOU1000000155_S0000030	it doesn't really tell us how much cash flow we might expect for that investors often rely on the fifty percent rule of thumb
YOU1000000155_S0000031	the fifty percent rule states that on average and over time half of the income in a property is spent on operating expenses
YOU1000000155_S0000032	now what our operating expenses well good question operating expenses are all of the expenses involved with running a rental property
YOU1000000155_S0000033	except the loan payment so it includes taxes insurance utilities repairs vacancy and other metrics
YOU1000000155_S0000034	that leave the landlord's checking account every single month or every year depends on how you want to look at it
YOU1000000155_S0000035	the fifty percent rule can help an investor quickly estimate the cash flow of a rental property because it combines all of those expenses except for the loan into one easy number
YOU1000000155_S0000037	so let's work through this imagine a property rents for two thousand dollars a month the fifty percent says half of this a thousand will be spent on expenses
YOU1000000155_S0000038	this means we're left with a thousand bucks but now we need to make the mortgage payment on this right unless you paid cash for the property but let's say you didn't
YOU1000000155_S0000039	so with that thousand dollars we have left let's say the mortgage is six hundred dollars so how much do you have left four hundred bucks
YOU1000000155_S0000040	because two thousand times fifty percent equals a thousand a thousand minus six hundred for operating expenses is four hundred dollars in cash flow
YOU1000000155_S0000041	that remaining number is what you can estimate over time on average you might get in monthly cash flow
YOU1000000155_S0000042	of course that fifty percent estimate on operating expenses can really vary wildly depending on the property
YOU1000000155_S0000043	in some areas taxes and insurance might be incredibly high but in other areas that might be much lower some properties require that the landlord pay all the utilities
YOU1000000155_S0000044	where other properties allow the tenant to pay their own and while inherent weaknesses do exist
YOU1000000155_S0000045	the fifty percent rule does have value i mean when you are looking at a property that rents for twelve hundred bucks a month
YOU1000000155_S0000047	and you know the mortgage payment would be around a thousand you can pretty much guarantee that property will not produce a positive cash flow
YOU1000000155_S0000048	because two hundred bucks a month is not a lot of room for all those expenses because twelve hundred times fifty percent equals six hundred
YOU1000000155_S0000049	six hundred minus a thousand is negative four hundred right now the fifty percent rule helps keep real estate investors in check
YOU1000000155_S0000050	and to remind us that there are a lot of expenses that over time add up yeah i mean a new roof is only needed every twenty years
YOU1000000155_S0000051	but if you divide a ten thousand dollars roof into two hundred forty months that roof is actually costing you forty-two bucks a month every single month
YOU1000000155_S0000052	these operating expenses add up over time and as most investors have seen they tend to settle around fifty percent giving a long enough time frame
YOU1000000155_S0000053	okay on to the final rule of thumb today the seventy percent rule
YOU1000000155_S0000054	the last couple of rules of thumb that we talked about we're designed to help rental property owners but what about the house flippers the wholesalers i don't want to leave you guys out
YOU1000000155_S0000055	so for those who are flipping houses the seventy percent rule can be helpful in determining just how much to pay for a property
YOU1000000155_S0000056	the seventy percent rule states that the most you should pay for a potential flip is seventy percent of the after repair value like what it would sell for when it was all fixed up
YOU1000000155_S0000057	minus the repair cost so example if a hole would sell for three hundred grand all fixed up and the property needed fifty grand worth of work to get there
YOU1000000155_S0000058	then three hundred thousand times seventy percent is two hundred ten thousand subtract out that fifty thousand dollar and you're left with one hundred sixty k
YOU1000000155_S0000059	according to the seventy percent rule the most someone should pay for that property would be a hundred sixty k but of course there are problems with the seventy percent rule
YOU1000000155_S0000060	this rule of thumb assumes that thirty percent of the a r v the after repair value is going to be spent on holding costs on closing costs on the buying side the selling side
YOU1000000155_S0000061	commissions taxes attorney fees title company fees and more and the flippers profit and any other charges that come up during the deal now this works well in some markets
YOU1000000155_S0000062	but it has some severe limitations
YOU1000000155_S0000063	for example the seventy percent rule doesn't really work that well for a property with a really low a r v after a pair of values
YOU1000000155_S0000064	such as fifty thousand dollars as mentioned earlier the thirty percent deducted from the a r v includes the holding cost and the closing cost as well as a profit
YOU1000000155_S0000065	the investor or the flipper wants to make however like thirty percent of fifty grand is like fifteen thousand dollar so following the seventy percent rule
YOU1000000155_S0000066	all of the fees cost and profit would only be fifteen grand
YOU1000000155_S0000067	if the fees and holding costs were to total like ten grand that would leave just five thousand dollar in profit for the house flipper
YOU1000000155_S0000068	and i don't know any house flipper who's gonna take on the risk of flipping a house for just five grand
YOU1000000155_S0000069	so following the seventy percent rule a flipper or wholesaler would pay far too much for the property in this example
YOU1000000155_S0000070	an investor flipping houses at this level might require far less than seventy percent maybe a fifty percent or even lower
YOU1000000155_S0000071	now a similar problem exists with the seventy percent rule for more expensive properties
YOU1000000155_S0000072	the seventy percent rule would dictate that a home with an a r v of seven hundred grand that needs fifty grand at work
YOU1000000155_S0000073	should produce a maximum offer of four hundred and forty thousand
YOU1000000155_S0000074	but in most markets finding a seven hundred dollar property for four hundred and forty thousand is simply not feasible
YOU1000000155_S0000075	a person who sticks exclusively to that seventy percent rule are likely never gonna find a good enough deal to ever flip in a single property in that market
YOU1000000155_S0000076	in this case eight percent or even eight-five percent might be good enough
YOU1000000155_S0000077	furthermore some investors may spend more or less on fees and costs because of their particular life situation or location
YOU1000000155_S0000078	for example in some states purchasing a home may require three grand in closing costs while in other states it might be six thousand dollars
YOU1000000155_S0000079	some investors may have a real estate license which saves them tens of thousands of dollars in commissions
YOU1000000155_S0000080	whereas other investors well they may need to pay commissions when they actually sell the property so how should the seventy percent rule be valued
YOU1000000155_S0000081	well carefully it's a quick and dirty way to guesstimate the approximate amount you should pay for a property
YOU1000000155_S0000082	but as with all rules of thumb no concrete decisions should be made unless you've run a real estate analysis on the property
YOU1000000155_S0000083	and of course if you want to do that check out the bigger pockets a suite of calculators you can get them at biggerpockets dot com forward slash calc c a l c
YOU1000000155_S0000084	check it out alright that's all i got if you liked this video make sure to give a thumbs up and subscribe to our channel be great we'll see you around the site around the community
