YOU1000000166_S0000069	does that translate to years as we understand them here on earth and it appears like it does according to wikipedia the republic's standardized it's time based on coruscant
YOU1000000166_S0000070	which conveniently rotates its sun exactly once every three hundred and sixty five coruscantian days which are broken down themselves into twenty-four hour increments
YOU1000000166_S0000071	and then minutes that are incredibly close to our own minutes so when yoda says that he's nine hundred years old it's pretty close to what we think nine hundred years is
YOU1000000166_S0000072	and the mandalorian has every reason to be surprised that his fifty year old mark was still a baby
YOU1000000166_S0000073	so knowing that it's time to talk about the biology having such a long development period is more than just an interesting evolutionary quirk
YOU1000000166_S0000074	it actually tells us a lot about how tri-dactyls may have evolved over time mostly because it parallels a lot of our own human evolution
YOU1000000166_S0000075	you see most animals evolved to shorten the amount of time between birth and reproductive maturity so that they can go on and grow their population as fast as possible
YOU1000000166_S0000076	but that's not the only successful evolutionary strategy you may have noticed that us humans have incredibly long and particularly vulnerable childhoods
YOU1000000166_S0000077	when a baby giraffe is born it can stand almost almost almost right away so cute humans on the other hand not so much
YOU1000000166_S0000078	it is taking months if not a year for a baby human to actually get up on its feet so why do humans the smartest animals on the planet
YOU1000000166_S0000079	come out so useless
YOU1000000166_S0000080	well it turns out that the whole issue comes down to our brains you see our brainy heads and the fact that they're so fat have changed our entire course of human evolution
YOU1000000166_S0000081	our ancestors who many believe emerged from sub-saharan africa were among the first species of animals to stop walking around on four legs
YOU1000000166_S0000082	and start walking upon two our brains were big enough that we were able to logic out the idea that it took less energy to walk on two legs
YOU1000000166_S0000083	and it minimized our bald skins exposure to the extremely hot ground temperatures in those african deserts
YOU1000000166_S0000084	as newly bipedal people our evolution started favoring other members of our species who could also walk upright good for us natural selection at its finest
YOU1000000166_S0000085	but there's always a price to pay for innovation you see as we evolved to be more and more capable of walking
YOU1000000166_S0000086	and running around on two legs our bodies evolved to facilitate that and compensate for our changed center of gravity primarily doing this by narrowing our hips
YOU1000000166_S0000087	this in turn helped us to walk upright like champs and all of a sudden we had a problem that big fat head of ours was literally too big to be born
YOU1000000166_S0000088	sure we had ourselves a big brain but now there was nowhere for it to go because our hips were too narrow to accommodate birthing a head that huge
YOU1000000166_S0000089	so human evolution had to change again as the theory goes we started having babies earlier in their gestational period
YOU1000000166_S0000090	earlier at a time when the baby was still tiny and smushy and helpless which would be pretty darn bad for our survival except for one thing
YOU1000000166_S0000091	the heads were still small enough to squeeze up on out of there still a very painful process but now at least it was doable
YOU1000000166_S0000092	and then once the baby was on the other end there would be what's known as the fourth trimester
YOU1000000166_S0000093	an extra trimester of development that happens outside in the real world where we as parents would have to take care of that helpless newborn
YOU1000000166_S0000094	because technically it still should have been developing in the womb it just needed to be you know evicted from its home before it was too big to leave its door
YOU1000000166_S0000095	now let's take a look at her friendly yoda what features do we see well he's bipedal he's small with a disproportionately huge head for his highly evolved brain
YOU1000000166_S0000096	he's got a short highly efficient body with diminutive narrow features including his hips even looking at the basic character model
YOU1000000166_S0000097	you can see how in order to procreate the tri-dactyls would have to have themselves radically different proportions
YOU1000000166_S0000098	you could also see how having a big brain is a huge evolutionary advantage humans are so far at the top of the food chain that we protect other members of the food chain
YOU1000000166_S0000099	tri-dactyls in the star wars universe are the wisest and most powerful force users in the galaxy
YOU1000000166_S0000100	but the downside is that they like us are essentially born too early helpless for months if not years or until at least their dad makes them pay rent
YOU1000000166_S0000101	and their mom stops doing their laundry this theory continues to hold water if we look at infancy for humans versus infancy for tri-dactyls in their first two years
YOU1000000166_S0000102	human baby brains grow to seventy-five percent of their full adult size we don't know if this is the same for tri-dactyls
YOU1000000166_S0000103	but we do know that the proportions of human babies paralleled the proportions of baby yoda enormous head adorably tiny body
YOU1000000166_S0000104	besides making babies hilariously top-heavy these proportions also serve a function in an infancy
YOU1000000166_S0000105	human brains command up to eighty-seven percent of the total energy that the body uses at rest
YOU1000000166_S0000106	meaning that even while sleeping the body is diverting a massive amount of energy to growing the brain
YOU1000000166_S0000107	because of this the rest of the baby's growth legs behind the head where the brain is this according to the expensive tissue hypothesis
YOU1000000166_S0000108	we can see that baby yoda is an extreme version of this principle with a wildly huge and merchandisable head
YOU1000000166_S0000109	and a teeny tiny body making me think that baby yoda is an extremely evolved version of what the human race could look like someday the
YOU1000000166_S0000111	process of evolutionarily elongating the development period is called neoteny
YOU1000000166_S0000112	and after humans benefited from it surviving when our relatives didn't well evolution didn't stop its roll
YOU1000000166_S0000113	humans are actually still experiencing longer development periods now than we even did ten thousand years ago
YOU1000000166_S0000114	the shape of our faces and heads are continually becoming less like our neanderthal cousins by becoming flatter less hairy less oblong
YOU1000000166_S0000115	again we share a lot of these same features with yoda who's small flat faced with an enormous head but if human evolution continues to make our childhoods longer and longer
YOU1000000166_S0000116	the question of course becomes where does it stop well it stops at yoda
YOU1000000166_S0000117	the problem with a long childhood is that a lot can happen when you're tiny and helpless
YOU1000000166_S0000118	eventually there's an evolutionary tipping point where childhood becomes so long that it actually leaves the species too vulnerable to survive into adulthood
YOU1000000166_S0000119	tri-dactyls could very well be the extreme end point of a species like ours
